<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Central Bank Raises Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada's central bank raised
interest rates by one percentage point to six percent Thursday in
a desperate move to prop up its battered currency.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Canadian dollar made a new record
Wednesday, dropping below 64 cents U.S. for the first time in its
140-year history.
</P>
<P>
During the past six months alone, the dollar has lost about 10
percent of its value against the strong U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
With the rate hike, the bank's operating band for the overnight
rate was similarly adjusted to a range of five to six percent.
</P>
<P>
"Today's increase in interest rates is aimed at providing
support for the Canadian dollar in order to bolster confidence,
while preserving monetary conditions that will help to sustain the
present non-inflationary expansion of the economy," the bank said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian dollar has been under persistent downward
pressure, which reflected an adjustment to increased economic
uncertainty in Asia, the associated downward pressure on the
prices of the primary commodities that Canada exports, and the
developing problems in Russia, it said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the currency decline has more recently developed a
momentum that, together with the upper pressure on medium and
longer-term interest rates, signals a diminishing of confidence in
Canadian dollar investments," it said.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, the depreciation of the currency has
resulted in a substantial easing of monetary conditions. While
some of this easing has been warranted by economic developments,
it is the bank's view that it has become excessive," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Canada has been resisting calls of interest rates
hike for fear of slowing the economy.
</P>
<P>
Despite its constant market interventions, the bank has failed
so far to halt the continuing slide of the Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian dollar was trading as low as 63.5 cents U.S. early
Thursday, which meant that in a 24-hour period it had dropped more
than one percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
