<HEADLINE> No More Aid for Russia without Reforms, Kohl Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
warned Thursday that Russia could not count on further financial
help, either from Germany or international financial institutions,
if it did not push through necessary economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Berlin on Thursday, Kohl said he is
"considerably concerned" about the recent financial turmoil in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he has kept frequent contact with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and is also planning to speak to U.S.
President Bill Clinton, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
French President Jacques Chirac about the situation in Russia.
</P>
<P>
As Russia's financial crisis continues to spin out of control,
there is growing alarm in Germany that the Russian turmoil could
soon have damaging economic consequences for the world economy and
hence for Germany, which is Russia's leading trade partner and
biggest lender.
</P>
<P>
Although the German government has been trying to convince
investors that any economic meltdown in Russia would only have
minor repercussions for Germany, some economists have warned that
if panic in Moscow triggers further instability in Asia and
Eastern Europe, the impact could be more devastating.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
