<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Rescuers Begin to Search Missing Climbers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- An eight-member Hong Kong
rescueing team has begun searching for three missing Hong Kong
climbers on Mt. Bogda when they set up a camp at 3,800 meters on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two rescueing experts, Chinese Mountaineering
Association Vice-President Li Zhixin and Dr. Ma Zhixiang, flied
to Urumqi to co-ordinate the rescueing work.
</P>
<P>
Chan King-chuen, Lam Chi-wai and Yeung Chi-ho have been lost
in snowstorms since August 16 when they attempted to scale the
5,445-meter peak in the Xinjiang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The rescue team came from Hong Kong's Ngok Fung Rock Climbing
Society, of which the missing trio are members.
</P>
<P>
An Chinese Army "Black Hawk" helicopter searched the mountain
area at 5,100-5,200 meters on Saturday but failed to spot the
trio.
</P>
<P>
Another group of rescuers dispatched earlier by Xinjiang
Mountaineering Association only found an empty tent with
equipments buried in snow at 4,700 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
