<HEADLINE> Gullit Takes over Newcastle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Former Dutch international and
Chelsea manager Ruud Gullit replaced Kenny Dalglish as manager of
Newcastle United on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced on the London stock market, which
had seen the publicly listed club's shares climb over 10 percent
to 64p as rumors of Gullit's arrival strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Dalglish, who took over from Kevin Keegan in January 1997,
offered his resignation nine days ago, prompting the club to
approach Gullit, who was sacked by Chelsea in February and has
been out of management since then.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch's agent, Phil Smith, told BBC Radio that Gullit met
Newcastle directors in Amsterdam on Monday when he agreed in
principle to take over, pending the release of Dalglish.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle issued a statement on Thursday saying that Dalglish
had offered to stand down on August 18, three days after the
first game of the season - a 0-0 home draw with Charlton when the
team was booed off the pitch.
</P>
<P>
Dalglish said he did not want to leave until a replacement was
arranged.
</P>
<P>
Gullit's first match in charge will be Sunday's home game
against Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
Gullit has been out of the game since he was surprisingly
sacked by Chelsea in February, after leading them to their first
major trophy for 26 years, the 1997 F.A. Cup. He was the first
overseas coach to win one of English soccer's major trophies.
</P>
</TEXT>
