<HEADLINE> Taliban Reject U.S. Talks Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Taliban Chief representative
based in Islamabad Saeedur Rahman has twice rejected the
telephonic requests by U.S. embassy officials for talks, the News
Network International quoted diplomatic sources as saying
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We had received two phone calls from the U.S. embassy, seeking
appointment with ambassador Saeedur Rahman, but the request was
turned down twice," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the U.S. embassy are making requests for talks
on the basis of diplomatic contacts but Rahman expressed inability
to spare time for them, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
"There is no justification for talks with the Americans after
they launched air strikes in Afghanistan in violation of
international law and norms," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the U.S. embassy said Tuesday that the U.S. was
ready to talk with the Taliban militia on Osama bin Laden and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
Top Taliban leader Muhammad Omar has already rejected the U.S.
offer for talks on Saudi dissident Osama. The Taliban militia have
ruled out any possibility of handing over Osama who is now in the
Taliban-controlled area in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
