<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Steps up Pressure on Libya over Lockerbie Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government
Thursday stepped up pressure on Libya over Lockerbie bombing case,
calling on the Libyan government to hand over the two Libyan
bombing suspects to stand for trial in Hague.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told reporters early
Thursday: "I welcome the Libyan response. As far as it goes it is
the most positive response we have had for the last seven years."
</P>
<P>
"But it doesn't meet the acid test of handing over the two
accused to the Netherlands and until we get that, we can't be too
confident or too optimistic about any response."
</P>
<P>
The Libyan Foreign Ministry said Wednesday that it would
"respond positively" to the joint Anglo-American proposal but did
not specifically say Libya had accepted it.
</P>
<P>
Cook also noted that Britain wanted to see a trial start as
soon as possible, reaffirming if the two Libyans were handed over
for trial, Britain would support the suspension of international
sanctions against Libya.
</P>
<P>
Some 270 people were killed when a Pan AM airliner exploded
over the Scottish town of Lockerbie on December 21, 1988 and the
U.N. imposed strict international sanctions against Libya in 1992
after the Libyan government refused to hand over the alleged
bombers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
