<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Tourism Hurt by Bombing: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The South African
Environment and Tourism Ministry is to consult government's
tourism safety task group on ways of thwarting further acts of
terrorism, Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He condemned Tuesday's blast at Cape Town's waterfront, a
popular tourism destination, as a senseless act of terrorism that
also inflicted untold damage on the economy.
</P>
<P>
"This act of terrorism, seen within the global context, hurts
our country's tourism industry," he said. "Those responsible for
this blast clearly acted to harm our country and its people."
</P>
<P>
One person was killed and 27 injured in the powerful bomb
blast in a U.S.-franchised restaurant at 7:20 p.m. local time
Tuesday. It appeared to be linked to U.S. strikes against
alleged Muslim terrorists in Sudan and Afghanistan last week.
</P>
<P>
Among the wounded are five of a British family of six, who
arrived at Cape Town Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The British government has advised all British nationals to be
vigilant when visiting South Africa, noting that there were high
levels of violence in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy in South Africa also asked American citizens
in the country to take extra precautions.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is an important industry in South Africa and Cape Town
is a major tourist attraction in the country.
</P>
<P>
The tourism safety task group run by the Tourism Ministry,
includes representatives of the police, the Foreign Ministry,
South African Tourism Board (Satour) and private sector
organizations.
</P>
<P>
It aims to find ways of making South Africa a safer
destination for tourists and creating a better overseas image of
this country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Men Killed in Somalia Amid Insecurity Posed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The various types of weapons
including large explosives, land mines and hand grenades continue
posing mortal threats and increasing insecurity to the Somalis
around the country.
</P>
<P>
Two men were killed and another seriously wounded in the
Huriwa district of the capital Mogadishu controlled by faction
leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred when a hand grenade carried by one of
the deceased exploded inside a garage near the SOS hospital at
about 10:00 am local time.
</P>
<P>
The seriously wounded man has been rushed to Ali Hassan
private clinic for treatment where his condition is reported to
be serious, but stable.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the explosion is not clear. However, several
men inside the same garage said the hand grenade was a bad one
and its holder never believed it would trigger off. Some
believed the bomb was heated up by the hot temperature inside the
garage.
</P>
<P>
Exactly ten days ago, two men were killed and four others
wounded when a similar hand grenade exploded inside a mosque in
the southern port town of Kismaio, 500 km south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to people inside the mosque which is at the heart of
the town, the hand grenade exploded after it fell off the pocket
of one of the men as the worshippers tried to kneel down for
prayer. The owner of the grenade, a weapon seller, had himself
killed on the spot.
</P>
<P>
Carrying hand grenades has been a fashion especially in
Mogadishu nowadays as the number of gangs and looters increases
in the streets of the capital. Hand grenades are also used by
women selling kat as a threat against the bandits getting close
to them with pistols in an attempt to intimidate them.
</P>
<P>
Three people have been killed in separate incidents in the
capital since Wednesday. The reason for the shooting is
reportedly related to a new rivalry by two groups of gunmen in
the area.
</P>
<P>
As insecurity is everywhere, Radio Galkaio quoted a circular
by Colonel Abdullahi Yuss-uf Ahmed, the so-called president of
the disputed Puntland authority, ordered his ministers and the
commanders of the police stations Wednesday to take a firm step
against anyone seen to be erecting a roadblock.
</P>
<P>
The five-point circular prohibits all roadblocks in and
outside the towns and calls on people to implement the new
circular which also states that all culprits will be subjected to
Islamic courts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Condemns Acts of Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
severely condemned the dastardly acts of violence against the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, a news release from the Foreign
Ministry said here Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The release said that Sri Lanka believes that no terrorist or
terrorist group should be afforded safe haven anywhere.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka also believes that the struggle against terrorism
would be most effective when carried out in pursuance of the
collective will of the international community, not by unilateral
action but in full conformity with international law, the
principles of the U.N. Charter and respect for the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of all States, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the release said the Sri Lankan government also
extends their deepest sympathies to the innocent people of
Afghanistan and Sudan who have been affected by the loss of life
in consequence of the recent attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
