<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's U.S.-Linked Businesses Tighten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Security is being
tightened at American-style restaurant chains in South Africa and
elsewhere in the world after Tuesday's blast in a U.S.-franchised
restaurant in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The powerful bombing in the Planet Hollywood restaurant in a
busy leisure complex claimed one life and left 27 injured,
including international tourists, The Star paper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A McDonald official said security guards have been deployed in
all 45 McDonald's burger chain stores in South Africa, and they
are granted the latitude to search people.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director Darryl Webb said staff had been briefed on
security risks.
</P>
<P>
"The security officials in all our restaurants are to make our
customers and staff comfortable," he said. "We will maintain
these measures for as long as we believe it is necessary."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German police said security was being tightened at
facilities with links to the United States, including Planet
Hollywood restaurants and U.S. diplomatic and cultural
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Planet Hollywood headquarters in Florida, the United States,
has recommended security measures be stepped up at the branch in
Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
The South African TGI Friday restaurant chain said more
security guards would be employed at their two shops.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director Sherief Keffeba said he had been talking to
other American companies and, while they did not expect any
problems, they planned to take matters seriously.
</P>
<P>
Keffeba said staff had been briefed on procedures in the event
of bomb attacks and other breaches of security.
</P>
<P>
Tricon Restaurants International, whose South African brands
are Kentucky Fried Chicken and Pizza Hut, said it was reviewing
its options and would not be instituting more security measures
at its 370 shops at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola Southern Africa said security at the company's
factories and offices would be increased.
</P>
<P>
Some local restaurants, scared of similar attacks on their
chains, quickly declared they are not American.
</P>
<P>
Spur Steak Ranches, a popular local food chain whose
advertized images are easily associated with the United States,
released a statement Wednesday, saying the company has nothing to
do with Americans except for its red Indian theme.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
