<HEADLINE> Arafat Not Optimistic About Advancement of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat is not optimistic over the chances
to advance the stalled peace process, an Israeli legislator who
met Arafat Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting in the West Bank town of Ramallah, Arafat told
Israeli Labor Knesset (Parliament) Member Salah Tarif that based
on the conditions imposed by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, there is still a long way to go before an agreement
could be reached over the long overdue Israeli redeployment in the
West Bank, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's remarks were made several days after he sounded an
optimistic note on the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations over an
American proposal which calls for Israel to withdraw its troops
from an additional 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
When attending a ceremony marking the fifth anniversary of the
Oslo Accords in Norway, Arafat declared Monday that the latest
Israeli withdrawal proposals could be "a beginning" toward an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that in a written proposal given to the
Palestinians last week, Israel suggested that it withdraw from 10
percent of the West Bank and turn another 3 percent into a "nature
reserve" where the Palestinians would not be allowed to settle.
</P>
<P>
In an exchange for a possible Palestinian concession, Israel
reportedly gave up one of its key demands. It would not insist
that the Palestinian National Council (PNC) be reconvened, before
any agreement is to be reached, to annul those articles in the
Palestinian Covenant which calls for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli officials played down the optimism, saying there
is no development to indicate progress towards an
agreement. Netanyahu has also denied that Israel has given up its
demand on the reconvening of the PNC.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tarif told Israel Radio that Arafat condemned the
bombing attack Thursday morning in Tel Aviv which injured more
than 20 people, saying the PNA is taking measures to prevent any
violence against civilians.
</P>
<P>
Israel has accused Arafat of failing to publicly condemn the
two recent killings of Jewish settlers in the West Bank. Two
Jewish settlers were killed in a settlement near the West Bank
town of Nablus early this month and one rabbi was stabbed to
death in his home in Hebron a week ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
