<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets Over Draft Lockerbie Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Thursday went on with its meeting over a draft resolution,
introduced by America and Britain, one day after Libya announced
its acceptance of a American-British proposal on the trial of two
Lockerbie suspects in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council went ahead with consultations
on the draft resolution despite Libyan earlier Wednesday asked
for a delay any council decision on the proposed resolution.
</P>
<P>
Later Wednesday, the Libyan Government said that it would
accept the U.S.-UK offer that the two Libyan suspects in the
bombing of an American airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
December 1988. The blast claimed 270 lives, including 11 people
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
More details of the U.S.-UK proposal were revealed here
Thursday as the Security Council circulated as a document the
letter to the U.N. Secretary-General, dated August 24, from the
American and British acting permanent representatives to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that the two suspected Libyans would be tried
in the Netherlands by a Scottish court under normal Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a Scottish court and would follow normal Scots law
and procedure in every respect, except for the replacement of the
jury by a panel of three Scottish High Court judges," the letter
said. "The Scottish rules of evidence and procedure, and all the
guarantees of fair trial provided by the law of Scotland, would
apply."
</P>
<P>
The letter assured Libya of the safe passage of the two
suspects, and said that if found guilty, the two Libyans would
serve their sentence in Scotland,
</P>
<P>
In announcing its acceptance of the offer, the Libyan Government
also demanded a fair and just trial, and a complete end of the
sanctions imposed on it in 1992.
</P>
<P>
It remains unknown of the specific location of the trial to be
held in the Netherlands, accepted by Tripoli as "a neutral third
country." Diplomatic sources here said the Dutch authorities had
offered three sites to try the suspects, but The Hague, which
was originally thought of, was not among them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Reiterates Commitment to Defend Cyprus Militarily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Thursday reiterated its
commitment to defend Cyprus militarily in the event of a threat.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued after a two-hour talks between
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis and visiting Cyprus President
Glafcos Clerides, Simitis said that the Greek government made it
clear to all that the Greek and Cypriot joint defense doctrine was
not restricted to defense planning, it constituted a commitment on
the part of Greece, the core of which was the Greek government's
decision to defend Cyprus militarily in the event of a threat.
</P>
<P>
Clerides, who arrived in Athens Wednesday for a two-day visit,
said that he was completely satisfied with his talks and welcomed
in particular Simitis's statement that any threat against Cyprus
would be confronted jointly.
</P>
<P>
On the deployment of Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles
in Cyprus, both sides stressed that there had been no decision to
postpone deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
While stressing that the S-300 missiles were purely defensive,
they said that neither government wanted friction or tension and
that their only concern was to strengthen Cyprus' defenses in the
face of Turkey's constantly growing provocactiveness and extensive
modernization of Turkish armaments in northern Cyprus, which has
been occupied by Turkey since 1974.
</P>
<P>
The essence of the Cyprus problem had nothing to do with one
kind of weapons or the other, it was a problem of invasion and
illegal occupation, Simitis pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders said that Greece and Cyprus fully supported the
efforts of the U.N. Secretary-General to find a solution within
the framework of the Security Council resolutions and the summit
agreements reached by the Greek-Cypriot and Turkish-Cypriot sides
in 1977 and 1979.
</P>
<P>
They urged the international community to continue its efforts
towards a resumption of inter-communal dialogue on the divided
island and the commencement of a dialogue on reducing arms and the
island's demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
Both men said that the two countries would not have any
objection in principle to a guaranteed military flight prohibition
zone over Cyprus, provided this was within the U.N. framework and
was part of a procedure which would lead to gradual disarmament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
