<HEADLINE> China Still Concerned Over Wording in Draft Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- China "supports in
principle" the U.N. Security Council's adoption of a draft
resolution, but still "has concerns over some wording" in the
resolution, offered by America and Britain, a Chinese diplomat
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Ranfeng, spokesman for the Chinese U.N. mission, told
Xinhua that "we support in principle the adoption of the draft
resolution, but we still have concerns over some wording" in the
draft.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "we want the present draft resolution to be improved
and more balanced," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council began another day of informal
consultations on the draft resolution, which is expected to
endorse a U.S.-UK plan to try the two suspected Libyans of the
Lockerbie bombing in the Netherlands, sources here said.
</P>
<P>
China has some reservations on some wording in the eighth
paragraph of the draft resolution, which said that the Security
Council would "consider additional measures if the two accused
have not arrived or appeared for trial promptly," said the
spokesman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
