<HEADLINE> Kohl Rebuts Handover Rumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
Thursday dismissed speculations that he might not serve a full
four-year term if he is re-elected in the September general
elections.
</P>
<P>
"I'm running for four years," Kohl told reporters in Berlin,
adding that "If I says I'll do something, I'll do it."
</P>
<P>
Kohl, 68, has been German chancellor since 1982. He is running
for an unprecedented fifth term against the chancellor candidate
of the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD), Gerhard
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
The latest speculations about Kohl's early retirement was
triggered by his designated successor, Wolfgang Schaeuble, who
told the German weekly Die Woche that the chancellor was running
for a full term but did not completely rule out handing over power
before 2002.
</P>
<P>
Kohl formally named Schaeuble, the 55-year-old parliamentary
leader of his Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party, as his
designated successor in October last year, but he never specified
when the handover should take place.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday Kohl stressed he could fully imagine that
Schaeuble would become CDU's chancellor candidate in the 2002
general elections.
</P>
<P>
However, as the 1998 election day is approaching, Kohl is still
fighting an uphill battle against Schroeder whom he is trailing
between three to six percentage points in opinion polls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
