<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Thursday welcomed the signing of a cease-fire
agreement between the Government of Guinea-Bissau and the
self-proclaimed junta.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire agreement was signed on July 26 in Praia, Cape
Verde Islands, in which the two sides agreed that Bissau airport
would reopen, enabling refugees to return home and humanitarian
aid to be distributed, and facilitating logistical support for a
mission supervising the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to hold a further round of talks in Abidjan
on September 11 and 12 to discuss the deployment of observers to
supervise the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued through his spokesman's office, Annan,
now in vocation in Africa, noted that the meeting between the two
sides to the conflict was held under the joint auspices of the
Economic Community of West African States and the Community of the
Portuguese-speaking Countries.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief expressed the hope that the two groups would
continue their joint efforts to help achieve lasting peace in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The military revolt against the rule of Guinea-Bissau
President Joao Bernardo Vieira led by former armed forces
commander Ansumane Mane broke out on June 7. 
</P>
