<HEADLINE> War Not Likely Between Greece and Turkey, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Deputy Foreign Minister
of Sweden Pierre Schori Friday ruled out the possibility of a war
between Greece and Turkey, saying that only crazy people would
contemplate something of the sort.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in the northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki, Schori said that there was a problem of dialogue
between the two countries, but this was not a new problem and a
war between the two neighbors was impossible, the Macedonian Press
Agency (MPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
As for the Kosovo crisis, he said that Sweden backed an
increased autonomy within the framework of the Yugoslav
Federation.
</P>
<P>
He called on Belgrade to stop its military actions in Kosovo
while pointing out that the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) would not
win their armed struggle in seeking independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the spread of the Asian and Russian economic
crisis to the European Union (EU), the minister stressed that the
European countries were not in any danger as in view of the
economic and monetary union their economies fulfill strict terms
allowing them to cope with international competition.
</P>
<P>
Schori is in Thessaloniki as part of the Swedish Social
Democrat Party's election campaign because some 20,000 Swedes are
now living in Greece with the right to vote in the Swedish
elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
