<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Resumes Ambitious Tibetan Railway Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- China has re-started an
ambitious plan to build the first railway in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, which was abandoned a decade ago, according to Legqog,
Chairman of the Regional People's Government.
</P>
<P>
Legqog, who has been in Guiyang, the capital of Guizhou
Province, for a regional economic coordination forum for 6
southwestern provinces and autonomous regions and Chongqing
Municipality, said that leaders at the meeting have asked the
central government for an early start on the project.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is the only provincial-level administrative region that
has no railway. Since the 1950s, Chinese engineers have been
planning and studying its prospects, and have proposed 4 routes
from Qinghai, Gansu, Sichuan, and Yunnan provinces.
</P>
<P>
One of them, from Qinghai to Tibet, was even started in the
1970s, but it came to a halt in the '80s, when it proved too
difficult and costly to complete, after the section from Xining,
the capital, to Golmud was finished in 1984.
</P>
<P>
This year, the central government's decision to increase
spending has rekindled Tibetans' hope for having their own
railway, Legqog said. Over the next 5 years, 70 billion yuan will
be spent on railways in the southwestern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Railway Ministry's No.1 Exploration and Design Institute
has completed a feasibility study on the 1,100-kilometer-long
section from Golmud to Lhasa, the capital of Tibet, which will
cost 13.9 billion yuan. They are expected to conduct a feasibility
study on a second option from Dali in Yunnan Province to Lhasa,
which is 710 kilometers long and is expected to cost 63.5 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The second route will put Tibet closer to the sea than the
first, and can link the Tibetan railway with two proposed railways
from China to Thailand and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Hua Maokun, the Ministry's engineer-in-chief, is cautious about
the project and says that it needs to be carefully studied and
that people should be patient and not in a hurry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
