<HEADLINE> Libya Sees Offer Acceptance as "Serious Position" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
United Nations, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Libya late on Thursday
voiced its acceptance to the American-British offer to try the two
suspected Libyans in the Netherlands, saying that it is hoped that
other parties concerned would be serious in its position.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Abuzed Dorda, Libyan permanent
representative to the United Nations, took the floor Thursday
night before the U.N. Security voted 15-0 to adopt a resolution,
introduced by the U.S. and UK, which endorsed a plan on changing
venue for the Lockerbie trial.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan Government's acceptance "is a serious position, an
irreversible position, " the Libyan envoy said, "We hope the other
parties will likewise be serious in its position."
</P>
<P>
Dorda said that the Libyan Government had the duty and right to
consider the different procedural legal issues pertaining to the
trial. "We are prepared on our part to undertake that
consideration either directly with the judicial authorities of the
states concerned or with the Secretary-General of the United
Nations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council adopted the resolution one day
after Tripoli announced its acceptance to the American-British
plan to try the two accused in the Netherlands by Scottish judges
under normal Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
However, the just-adopted resolution said that the Security
Council would "consider additional measures" if Libya failed to
promptly hand over the two suspected.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused of blowing up an American airliner
over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988, which killed a total
of 270 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
