<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Income Picks Up 0.5 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Personal income in the United
States picked up 0.5 percent in July, to a seasonally adjusted
7.14 billion dollars, but Americans seem to spend less for the
first time in over two years, the Commerce Department reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wages and salaries, which account for more than half of
Americans' income rose 0.6 percent in July, reflecting continued
low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
But factory wages dropped 0.5 percent and farmers' income fell
5.5 percent, indicating that economic crises in Asia may be
affecting American commerce.
</P>
<P>
However most other income categories, including service and
distributive industry wages, business owners' income, rents and
transfer payments such as Social Security, went up.
</P>
<P>
After-tax personal incomes in June rose by only 0.2 percent,
but consumer spending remained high, rising by 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, personal consumption expenditures fell 0.2
percent, the first decline since June 1996, to a seasonally
adjusted rate of 5.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Those factors pushed the nation's personal savings rate in June
down to a revised 0.1 percent, the lowest since the government
began keeping monthly statistics in 1959.
</P>
<P>
In July, after-tax personal income rose 0.5 percent, the same
increase as the overall income figure. Combined with lower
spending, that brought the savings rate back up to 0.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Bonnie Regains Power Off U.S. Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Bonnie regained
strength Thursday night and pelted the Virginia coast with
torrential rains and howling winds early Friday, leaving two
people dead and hundreds of thousands of residents without
electricity.
</P>
<P>
Heavy wind and rain flooded roads, sent waves crashing over the
beachfront boardwalk and toppled trees and power lines.
</P>
<P>
A 12-year-old girl was killed in Currituck County, North
Carolina, near the Virginia border, when a tree fell on her
family's home. A 50-year-old man was electrocuted near Myrtle
Beach, South Carolina, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
In Norfolk's Ocean View section, Virginia, wind peeled the
roofs off a 30-unit apartment building and a three-story motel.
Several other buildings were damaged. The 29-kilometer Chesapeake
Bay Bridge-Tunnel connecting Virginia Beach to the Eastern Shore
peninsula was closed.
</P>
<P>
About 266,000 Virginian customers and about 129,000 residents
in eastern North Carolina were without power on Friday, but local
utilities projected most would have electric service restored by
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
People evacuated from the storm or unable to return home were
still housed in 43 shelters along the coast.
</P>
<P>
After making landfall on Wednesday along Cape Fear, North
Carolina. as a powerful hurricane packing 185 kph winds, Bonnie
overnight tracked across the Outer Banks and back out into the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
At 8 a.m. EDT (1200 GMT), the storm was centered about 144
kilometers southeast of Wallops Island, Virginia, and was moving
slowly northeastward, with its eye off the North Carolina-Virginia
coast.
</P>
<P>
It was expected to begin moving to the northeast along the
Atlantic coast Friday before veering by southern New England
Friday night and Saturday. Coastal residents were warned to
prepare for rain and high wind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
