<HEADLINE> All Abroad Missing Myanmar Airliner Feared Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The crew members and 36
passengers on board a missing airliner of state-run Myanmar
Airways, which was found Thursday crashed in a dense forest under
a mountain in Myanmar's eastern Shan state, are all feared dead,
state-owned Radio Myanmar reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Armed Forces Thursday night discovered the Fokker F-27
aircraft XY-AEN 16 kilometers northeast of Tachilek in the state
bordering Laos and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Rescue work is underway by the Myanmar authorities, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that a special investigation board has been formed to
look into the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
An earlier official report said that Lao government officials
informed the Myanmar government Thursday that the missing Myanmar
airliner had been found crashed in the Payakha mountain in the
north of Laos.
</P>
<P>
The Fokker aircraft lost its way over Tachilek when it was on a
domestic flight from Yangon to Tachilek Monday morning with 36
local passengers aboard.
</P>
<P>
The Tachilek airport traffic control tower lost contact with
the aircraft when it failed to land at an altitude of 3,000 meters
due to bad weather condition. The plane had attempted to turn back
to a nearby airport, the Heho. 
