<HEADLINE> Iraqi Kurdish Faction Kills Turkey's Kurdish Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi Kurdish faction have
killed 269 of Turkey's Kurdish rebels in northern Iraq over the
past eight months, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a radio report by Iraq's Kurdish Democratic Party
(KDP) as saying that the rebels of the Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK), outlawed in Turkey, were mostly killed during their raids
on villages in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting for independence in southeast Turkey
since 1984, while Turkish troops were trying every way to wipe out
the militants.
</P>
<P>
About 2,500 PKK members have been taking shelters in northern
Iraq since Baghdad was rendered ineffective in controlling the
area in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The KDP radio said its forces launched counterattacks against
PKK militants who looted villages and killed some of them. It also
said that 20 PKK guerrillas were captured in clashes in August.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the KDP has been cooperating with Turkish troops
and helping them to uproot the PKK, who used northern Iraq as a
springboard for attacks against Turkish targets across the
border. 
</P>
