<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Stop Deterioration Of Water Ecology (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- China's State Environmental
Protection Administration said today that China will try to stop
the ecological deterioration in major river and lakes as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The director of the administration's Nature Protection
Department says that China will monitor construction and
development in resource-rich areas and use legal, administrative,
economical, technical and educational means to prevent further
damage to the ecology.
</P>
<P>
China will clarify developers' ecological protection
responsibilities and that they will have to protect the area they
work in and rehabilitate it. Those who benefit from development
have to pay for restoration.
</P>
<P>
The official said that China will set up a number of reserves
to protect river sources and lakes and wetlands and the government
has decided to increase protection of natural forests which are
already threatened, and ban deforestation in forest and grassland
areas that have good water conservation possibilities.
</P>
<P>
The State Forestry Administration has also said that not a
single natural tree should be chopped down on the upper reaches of
the Yangtze River and that anyone who cuts trees needs to be
punished in accordance with the Forestry Law.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Province, on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River,
plans to stop deforestation from September 1 and will close all
lumber markets in the province. This means that the Chuanxi Forest
Area, with more than 4.6 million hectares of land, which is one of
the country's three major forest areas, will see no more axes and
saws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke082874 - Singapore's Manufacturing Output Dips 6.2 PCT in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The total manufacturing output
in Singapore declined 6.2 percent in July 1998 but its cumulative
output from January to July increased by 1 percent compared with
the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released Friday by the Economic Development Board
showed that in regard of output in July, electronics sector fell
12.8 percent, chemicals cluster increased 10.9 percent (with
pharmaceuticals up 68.4 percent, Petrochemicals up 4.3 percent,
petroleum products down 1.9 percent, industrial chemicals down
13.4 percent) and production of engineering cluster contracted by
5 percent (with precision engineering down 15.7 percent, process
engineering up 4.9 percent and transport engineering up 9.5
percent).
</P>
<P>
It also showed that in regard of the cumulative output from
January to July, the electronics products dropped by 3.3 percent,
chemicals sector grew by 15.2 percent (with pharmaceuticals up
38.5 percent, Petrochemicals up 23.4 percent, petroleum products
up 8.5 percent, industrial chemicals down 7.1 percent) and
production of engineering cluster increased by 4.4 percent (with
precision engineering down 6.0 percent, process engineering up
11.7 percent and transport engineering up 18.9 percent).
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing output fell by 4.1 percent in May and by 0.8
percent in June this year from a year ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
