<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Demand Increases in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Demand for foreign exchange
increased to 111.89 million U.S. Dollars this week from last
week's 74.27 million Dollars at the autonomous foreign exchange
market in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The This Day newspaper said Friday that this week's high level
of demand had been seen as realistic demand on the part of
foreign exchange users, especially the manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Ade Adefeko, Head of Treasury Department of Fidlity Union
Merchant bank, was quoted as saying that manufacturers are this
time around making effective demand to import some of their
important raw materials for production.
</P>
<P>
A demand analysis showed that foreign exchange demand under
letters of credit stood at some 99.87 million Dollars or 89.25
percent of the total while those made under the invisibles was
12.06 million Dollars or 10.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the high demand for foreign exchange
reflected investors' confidence in the country's economy due to
the reconciliatory political and economic policies taken recently
by Nigerian Federal Government.
</P>
<P>
In the last four weeks, the exchange rate of the local
currency Naira has been stable, standing at 84 Naira to one
Dollar, and observers here predicted that the rate stability
would continue for a long time.
</P>
<P>
Adefeko noted that most of the leakages in the economy
experienced during the Sani Abacha (the late head of state who
died of heart attack last June) days had been blocked, adding
that this had sanitized the foreign exchange market and hindered
speculative bidding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy Further Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' gross national
product (GNP) grew by a merely 0.6 percent during the first
semester this year, Economic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate was the lowest since the fourth quarter of 1992
when production was affected by the Gulf War, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, when compared with other economies also hit by the
Asian financial crisis, the rate was still better, Medalla said,
adding that Malaysia and South Korea posted a negative 7 percent
and 6.6 percent growth respectively during the second quarter
while Indonesian economy is expected to contract by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months this year, the Philippines' gross
domestic product (GDP) managed to post a positive growth of 0.2
percent with the help of the services sector.
</P>
<P>
The services sector, which comprises 20 percent of the overall
GDP growth, grew by 4.1 percent under the boost of communications,
especially the increase in telephone rates.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture and industry sectors recorded a negative 7.5
percent and zero growth compared with last year's growth of 3.4
percent and 6.3 percent. Agriculture plunged to its 20-year low
because of the El Nino drought.
</P>
<P>
"With this (GNP) growth (of 0.6 percent), the high-end of the
2-3 percent government target is virtually out of reach, but there
is still a chance that we are still within the range," Medalla
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the agriculture sector will perform better in the
second half because rains are expected to come during the period
when farmers will be harvesting their crops.
</P>
<P>
"If that happens, then we can have positive agricultural output
growths in the second semester. In this case, the lower end range
of the target is still feasible," he said.
</P>
<P>
This optimistic view about the economy was shared by central
bank governor Gabriel Singson. He said that with an improvement in
weather conditions and the continued decline in interest rates,
both the agriculture and the manufacturing sectors should perform
better.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the country's monetary policy will remain flexible
to accommodate higher credit growth without upsetting this year's
inflation target of 9.25-9.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We should be able to avoid a recession and maintain a
sustainable growth in 1999," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the Asian financial crisis, the Philippines' GNP
and GDP grew by 2.5 percent and 1.7 percent respectively during
the first quarter this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
