<HEADLINE> Opposition Parties Ask U.N. to Renew Its Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Two major opposition parties
Friday sent a letter to United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan to ask the U.N. to renew its commitment in assessing the
Cambodian elections.
</P>
<P>
The letter signed by Prince Ranariddh, president of Funcinpec,
and Sam Rainsy, president of Sam Rainsy Party (SRP), said they had
filed complaints to the Constitutional Council against the
National Election Committee (NEC) Friday in regard to two
critically important issues.
</P>
<P>
The complaints included the seat allocation formula and the
process that led to it and the NEC's failure to fulfil its duties
of hearing appeals and protests, according to the letter.
</P>
<P>
"We have been beset by pressures to negotiate with the ruling
party and form a coalition government. We feel that it would be
more appropriate that pressure should first be directed at the
ruling party," they added.
</P>
<P>
They asked Annan to help create a multilateral body to examine
the ongoing electoral process and to remain engaged in the
electoral process until a credible result is achieved and a
legitimate government is formed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they demanded the U.N. refrain from making any
further assessment of the electoral process as a whole until it
has reached its conclusion and also to transmit their requests to
other observation bodies so that the international community's
assessment was coordinated.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec and SRP have been started a massive sit-in protest
across from the National Assembly five days ago against the
election results and demanding the Second Prime Minister step down.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, charged the rally was illegal because
permission had not been sought. 
</P>
