<HEADLINE> Faction Convoy Ambushed in S. Somalia, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Reports from the southern
Somali region of Bay indicate that a convoy of battle wagons were
ambushed Friday near the town of Bur Hakaba, 215 km south of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the VHF radios, the battle wagons
consisting of four technicals and nearly 50 heavily armed
militiamen of Hussein Aidid's faction were on their way to the
capital from the town of Huddor when they were attacked just
outside Bur Hakaba town at about 10:00 a.m. local time Friday.
</P>
<P>
At least four militiamen were killed and more than three
others wounded during the exchange of the heavy gunfire between
Hussein Aidid's men and those suspected Rahanwein Resistance Army
(RRA) guerrilla fighters.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to Hussein Aidid's men said the convoy was
halted after one of the battle wagons ran out of fuel when they
noticed unidentified infantry gunmen surrounding them from all
sides.
</P>
<P>
However, sources said two battle wagons from the ambushed
technicals have managed to arrive in the capital in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen on board these technicals confirmed the
incident and reported to have seen one of the dead bodies of the
attackers lying by the tarmac roadside just after the shooting
had subsided.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know what else they had suffered, but they fled,"
said one of the militiamen.
</P>
<P>
However, unconfirmed reports said one of Hussein Aidid's
battle wagons was seized by the suspected RRA guerrilla fighters
during the exchange of the fire, a claim strongly denied by
Hussein Aidid's side.
</P>
<P>
But Hussein Aidid's men admitted to have lost three of their
gunmen who died on the spot during the ambush, while three others
suffered gunshot wounds. There has been no word as yet from the
RRA nor was there any official comment from Hussein Aidid's side
over the ambush.
</P>
<P>
The regions of Bay and Bakol remained calm these days despite
the continuous occupation by Hussein Aidid's militiamen since
late 1995 when late General Mohamed Farah Aidid invaded those
regions with the aim of wiping out a regional autonomous
administration established for the Rahanwein communities with the
help of UNOSOM (United Nations Operation in Somalia).
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid had pledged that he will withdraw his forces
from the two regions ten days prior to the anticipated Baidoa
conference in accordance with the Cairo peace declaration signed
in late last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
