<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Religious Leader (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said he thinks that grafting Western concepts onto Chinese
culture is not wise and that China has a proud heritage and should
never give it up, and went on to say that he doesn't see any
conflict between Confucianism, and any of the principles he
believes in.
</P>
<P>
"Confucius never told people about God," he says, but gave them
a philosophical way of living with each other, which is very
beneficial, and that he admires another philosopher Sun Wu, whose
"Art of War" is being studied very carefully by many people in the
U.S. today, and that a great deal can be learned from them.
</P>
<P>
He said he agrees that the world should have multiple systems
instead of one single system, and mentioned Deng Xiaoping's
bringing market-oriented economic reform to China, and that Deng
had the courage to move the Chinese economy toward a more modern
system, and that it was a brilliant move.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that there will be a triumph of wisdom and
not of any specific social system like American capitalism, and
that each society will have its own different role to play in a
world where "we want to live in peace." 
</P>
</TEXT>
