<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Thwarts Speculative Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has successfully
repelled international speculators when a two-week government
intervention in the stock market came to a showdown Friday, said a
high-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
The government intervention has pushed the Hang Seng Index up
about 1,200 points over the past two weeks, thwarting the
speculators' plan to profit from a sharp fall in the stock and
futures markets by dumping the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
"We have frustrated their plan," Financial Secretary Donald
Tsang told a press conference Friday shortly after the stock
market closed with a record high single-day turnover of nearly 80
billion HK dollars (10 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Instead of benefiting from a collapse of the Hang Seng Index,
the speculators had to settle their short positions in the index
futures ahead of the expire of the August futures contract
Friday, said Tsang.
</P>
<P>
He added that the speculators would also found it expensive to
roll their short positions in the Hang Seng Index futures from
August to September.
</P>
<P>
Though Hong Kong is reluctant in market intervention, Tsang
noted, adding "As a respectable and responsible government, we
must take all the necessary steps to protect the stability and
integrity of our currency and financial markets when they are
under speculative attacks."
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate between the Hong Kong dollar and the
greenback has been stable for the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said that the government will soon work out follow-up
policy measures to enhance Hong Kong's resilience to speculative
attacks.
</P>
<P>
On the monetary side, Tsang said, the government will make the
currency board system more transparent and open to boost public
confidence, but less susceptible to manipulative play.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is considering measures to make the
securities and futures markets less vulnerable to manipulative
practices.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung
Chee Hwa said at a separately held press conference here Friday:
"This was an operation thought through in Hong Kong, and decided
in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He said the move was necessary to enable Hong Kong to have a
stable interest rate environment for an economic recovery. Hong
Kong economy contracted 5 percent in the second quarter of 1998,
following a negative GDP growth of 2.8 percent in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Tung reaffirmed that the government still stands ready to
intervene whenever there is a clear linkage between speculation on
the currency market, and stock and futures markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Budget Revision Rejected by Some Ministries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Spending cuts stipulated in
Romania's 1998 budget revision has been rejected by several
ministries which are set to be hit hardest by the policy.
</P>
<P>
The rejections from the National Education, Health, Culture and
Transport ministries came Friday as the government began debate
over the draft ordinance on budget revision, which will axe funds
for ministries by 8,000 billion lei (about 900 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figure represented about 10 percent of the current budget
and two percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
As the spending cuts are the only way to cover part of the
budgetary deficit, all the ministers have formally accepted
it. But the agreement of principle over this measure was not
automatically accepted by the government members.
</P>
<P>
National Education Minister Andrei Marga said his ministry's
cuts of 1,000 billion lei (112 million dollars) "are absolutely
unacceptable and will have serious consequences on education".
</P>
<P>
Marga said that his ministry needed another 800 billion lei (90
million dollars) this year and could not accept any reduction.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Hajdu Gabor said the cuts of 100 billion lei
(11 million dollars) would be extremely painful for his ministry.
He specified measures such as cancelling investment, cutting
hospital spending and not filling vacancies.
</P>
<P>
Culture Minister Ion Caramitru showed no enthusiasm on his
ministry's budget revision, where spending will drop 74 billion
lei (8.3 million dollars), affecting investments.
</P>
<P>
National Defense Minister Victor Babiuc was also unhappy, for
his ministry will lose at least four percent of the given budget.
</P>
<P>
But the budget revision, proposed by Minister of Finance Daniel
Daianu, won the backing of Prime Minister Radu Vasile, who said,
"There is no other better solution and an increase in the budget
deficit cannot be accepted."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Daianu justified the revision, claiming there could
be a risk of the budget deficit jumping over 5.5 percent from the
initial target of 3.6 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the government said no decision had been made till
now over the issue and the draft ordinance would be discussed
during an extraordinary government session on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government has pressed ahead with unpopular
austerity policies aimed at overhauling the troubled economy which
witnessed a surge in inflation from 57 percent in 1996 to over 100
percent last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
