<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Still Easing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The continuing weakening of the
Australian dollar has failed to stop an easing in wool prices this
week, the Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the Australian dollar falling to an all-time low
against the U.S. dollar during the course of this week, this did
not have any positive effect on wool prices in Australian currency
terms," ACWE said in its weekly report.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, this further lowering of the spot cost of Australian
wool to our overseas customers will only increase the risk of
earlier contracts being dishonored."
</P>
<P>
ACWE said prices eased marginally at sales in Newcastle and
Fremantle.
</P>
<P>
"The eastern indicator fell three cents to 563 cents clean
based essentially on a drop of eight cents in the north, as in the
west there was no change in the regional indicator."
</P>
<P>
"Consequently the northern and western regional indicators
finished the week at 568 and 519 cents per kilogram clean
respectively."
</P>
<P>
With no sale in the south, the regional indicator remained at
557 cents per kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
ACWE noted that the smaller offering of 52,938 bales had failed
to hold the market steady.
</P>
<P>
"The continuing uncertainty over the stockpile decision is not
helping the situation and the worsening economic outlook in Asia
and other countries is impeding trade confidence."
</P>
<P>
If parliament did not meet next week to impose a legislative
freeze on the wool stockpile from October, then the principle area
of speculation would be what action Wool International would take
about its commitment to selling 90,000 bales in the December
quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
