<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say Peking Man Had Fire (1) by Yu Zheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese paleoanthropologists and
archaeologists say that ash and charcoal remains found in a cave
near Beijing prove that Peking Man was the first to use fire.
</P>
<P>
No place in the world can compare with Zhoukoudian (the site
where Peking Man was discovered) for evidence of the controlled
use of fire, according to Zhang Senshui, a research fellow with
the Chinese Academy of Sciences' Institute of Vertebrate
Paleontology and Paleoanthropology.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1920s, archaeologists have found hominid
fossils and primitive tools from as far back as 500,000 to 200,000
years ago at Zhoukoudian, in Beijing's southwestern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Burnt animal bones and charcoal remains found in the cave there
in the 1930s caused people to believe that Peking Man might be the
earliest ancestor of fire users.
</P>
<P>
But, some researchers were suspicious of this and suggested
that water might have carried the charred bones and ash into the
cave over time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peking And Fire (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Steve Weiner of Israel's Weizmann Institute of Science, who
was involved in 5 studies between 1994 and 1997 at Zhoukoudian,
wrote in the journal Science that no ash or charcoal remains could
be detected, so, although indirect evidence of burning is present,
there is no direct evidence.
</P>
<P>
But, Wu Xinzhi, a paleoanthropologist who works with Zhang,
says that Weiner and the other four researchers only examined some
sediment from the western section of Site 1 and that they did not
have enough evidence to support the claim that most of the
fine-grain sediment at the site came in with water laid, and that
even if ash remains could be recognized, it would be difficult to
demonstrate where they were produced.
</P>
<P>
Guo Shilun, a research fellow of the Atomic Energy Institute,
says that in the 1970s they examined samples from the cave using
fission track dating and concluded that they were the same age as
the sediment. If the ash was from burning, the rock inside the
cave would show a much older age.
</P>
<P>
The use of fire offered early ancestors protection against
large beasts, provided warmth, nutrition and light at night, and
experiments have shown that rocks and lithological units outside
the cave are at least 100 million years old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peking Man And Fire (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Running water might affect the aggregation in the cave in some
way because it was not enclosed so much, Zhang, who is a
specialist in Paleolithic artifacts, says, and the hearth was very
difficult to keep intact.
</P>
<P>
"I have no doubt about Peking Man's ability to use fire," says
Jia Lanpo, of CAS, who unearthed parts of Peking Man in the
1930s. He says he found charcoal grains in Layer 10 and even a
piece of charred Chinese redbud in the quartzite layer, about 10
centimeters long and thicker than his thumb.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhoukoudian's geology, the ash layer might be thin
or thick and there might be more than one, says Liu Dongsheng,
also of CAS's Geology Institute, and even forest fires can leave a
thin layer of black grains in loess.
</P>
<P>
The bones of tiny fauna might be moved by water, but water
could hardly wash heavy stone artifacts into the cave, Zhang adds,
and a heavy stone tool excavated from Layer 4 was obviously
burnt. The occurrence of ash, burnt bones, stone artifacts and
hominid fossils in the same layers prove cultural association, he
says.
</P>
<P>
The Peking Man site at Zhoukoudian is on UNESCO's World
Heritage list.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislators Say Cause Of Floods Should Be Made Clear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese legislators view
the nation-wide fight against floods with mixed feelings and say
that the causes of the disaster need to be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
At the 4th meeting of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress here today, 7 legislators said that more
attention should be paid to water conservation and environmental
deterioration, which are believed to be one of the major causes of
this year's flooding.
</P>
<P>
They said that from 1996 to 2000, about 300 billion yuan is
expected to be put into water conservation projects.
</P>
<P>
The destructive floods were caused by the excessive cutting of
trees on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River. The widespread
deforestation caused serious soil erosion on 570,000 square
kilometers of land.
</P>
<P>
Yao Zhengyan, a former vice minister of Water Resources, says
that China has built more than 80,000 reservoirs since 1949, and
that rivers with water conservation projects were in better
condition than those without. He said the central government needs
to put more money into water conservation projects and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Wan Shaofen says that the most important thing is to ensure a
basic living standard of people in the flood hit areas, and
control disease and provide help for students in those areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
