<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Suspend Credit to Subsidiaries of Five Conglomerates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government Friday
announced the suspension of credit to weak and nonviable
subsidiaries of the nation's five biggest conglomerates from next
month.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the National Assembly on Thursday, Lee
Hun-jai, chairman of the Financial Supervisory Commission, said
any subsidiaries of Hyundai, Daewoo, Samsung, LG and SK, which had
lost competitiveness would be subjected to the credit suspension.
</P>
<P>
The suspension measures included the halting of new loans,
refusal to extend maturing loans and withdrawal of existing loans,
Lee added.
</P>
<P>
The survival of the South Korean economy largely depends on the
competitive strength of the five family-owned conglomerates and
they should give up all nonviable and unprofitable businesses,
said government officials.
</P>
<P>
However, the five industrial giants said recently they had to
tackle many other issues, including strikes and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
South Korean conglomerates have been blamed for devouring bank
loans and shirking responsibility for producing the current
financial crisis with their high debts.
</P>
<P>
The subsidiaries of the nation's top 30 conglomerates were
laden with total debts of 28 billion U.S. dollars, which was 4.5
times more than their capital at the end of 1997 when the nation
signed an agreement with the International Monetary Fund for a
rescue loan of 58 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, South Korea has to restructure its economy
and open its markets this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
