<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Religious Leader Says Door To China Should Remain Open (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Pat Robertson, chairman of the
board of the U.S.'s Christian Broadcasting Network and founder of
the American Center of Law and Justice, told Xinhua in an
interview today that Sino-U.S. relations have entered a new era of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Robertson was concluding his fourth visit to China today. On
Wednesday, he met with Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji at Zhongnanhai,
the Chinese government compound for over an hour.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old Robertson was born in Lexington, Virginia, and
is a descendant of Benjamin Harrison, one of the signers of the
Declaration of Independence, and of two former U.S. Presidents.
</P>
<P>
When Robertson first visited China in 1979, he found a
"backward" nation that he said was "best characterized by masses
of somber people dressed in drab gray Mao jackets riding silently
on thousands of cheap, mass-produced bicycles."
</P>
<P>
He says that he learned then that the Chinese government owned
every means of production and distribution down to the smallest
kiosk and that the only free enterprises were those with
home-grown vegetables. A factory worker earned the equivalent of
28 U.S. dollars a month. The manager of a factory employing 2,000
people earned no more than 70 or 80 dollars per month, he
recalls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
