<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Religious Leader (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On subsequent visits, after the economic reforms begun by Deng
Xiaoping, however, Robertson found "something extraordinary", and
that China had become a "beehive" of commercial activity, with 220
million television sets, fiber optic television cables, cellular
phones, shops full of Western consumer goods, ultra-modern hotels
and office buildings, a fledgling stock exchange, roads with sleek
automobiles, construction projects going twenty-four hours a day,
seven days a week, and the largest McDonald's in the world. What
he saw was an emerging industrial giant.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said that he is very happy to see a new era of warm
cooperation taking place between the United States and China and
that he recently wrote an article for the Wall Street Journal
titled "Keep The Door To China Open", in which he said that
isolating China and hoping that China would never become a
super-power is like hiding under the covers and hoping that the
sun does not rise in the morning.
</P>
<P>
There is no question that Chinese society is a great deal more
open, he said, when asked about the progress China has made in the
past two decades,
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the live TV coverage of a debate between
President Jiang Zemin and visiting President Bill Clinton as a
historic event signifying great social progress and a great
movement toward freedom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
