<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Provide More Aid to Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
decided to provide a grant aid of 55,524 U.S. dollars to a Myanmar
association for a human resources development project under its
grass roots grant assistance program.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release of the Japanese Embassy here, the
grant aid contract for the project "Improvement of Promotion
Center for Out-of-School Village Girls" was signed Friday between
Japanese Ambassador to Myanmar Kazuo Asakai and the coordinator of
the Salesian Sisters Association.
</P>
<P>
The grant aid will be used to construct buildings and purchase
equipment for the center located in Pyin Oo Lwin, Mandalay
division, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1994-95 fiscal year up to the last 1997-98 fiscal
year, the Japanese government had provided a total of 349,363
dollars for eight human resources development projects in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Japanese government also provided a grant aid
of 5.7 million dollars to Myanmar to help it increase food
production in the border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
