<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares dived almost
100 points at the opening Friday before a surging AMP and slight
rally by the local dollar clawed back the stock market's loses to
1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 43.7 points down at
2,516.9 points after falling to 2,461.3 points in early trade with
plunging overseas markets buffeting the local bourse.
</P>
<P>
"If it wasn't for AMP, the market would be further down than it
is," said Morgan Stockbroking client adviser Kim Ferrier, "the
Australian dollar and AMP saved the day."
</P>
<P>
Still, the all ordinaries closed at its lowest level since
December 12 last year.
</P>
<P>
More than 7.34 million AMP shares were traded, with fund
managers buying up the stock before its listing on the Morgan
Stanley Capital Index next week.
</P>
<P>
On the local equities markets, the all industrials index closed
66.6 points lower at 4,471.8 points, while the all resources index
dropped 27.2 points to 930.8 points.
</P>
<P>
Against the negative market sentiment, Telstra rose five,
topping the turnover table with 70.3 million installment receipts
traded.
</P>
<P>
The "big four" banks all lost ground, with the industry index
plunging 130 points to 5,584.6 points.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank shed 65 cents, ANZ dropped 33, Westpac
slid 25 and the Commonwealth surrendered 14.7.
</P>
<P>
The gold index slumped 41.2 points to 871.9 points with losses
across the board as the spot price of gold bullion in Sydney
slumped sharply to 271.65 U.S. dollars an ounce, down from 281.15.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 461.38 million stocks changing hands
for 2.06 billion Australian dollars (1.153 billion U.S. dollars),
with falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks by 818 to 362.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
