<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of China Launches Investment Banking Arm in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Bank of China (BOC) launched
its investment banking arm, the new BOC International Holdings
Ltd. here Friday to streamline the bank's overseas investment
banking businesses.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of BOC International, previously based in
London, moved to the Special Administrative Region after more than
half year's ground work, winding up BOC's re-grouping of all its
overseas investment banking operations, Vice Chairman of BOC
International Liu Jinbao told a press conference Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Before BOC International's restructuring, BOC, a leading
state-owned commercial bank in China, had already been involved in
investment banking activities in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Now, under the new BOC International's umbrella, there are nine
subsidiaries offering all-round investment banking services
including securities business, asset management, project finance
and direct investment, said Liu, who is also general manager of
BOC Hong Kong Branch.
</P>
<P>
Liu pledged that BOC International will continue to provide
services to China's state-owned enterprises by facilitating their
restructuring of assets and debts, and guiding them to
international capital market.
</P>
<P>
BOC International aims to "grow into one of the first-class
investment banks in the region in the next three to five years,"
the banker said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the opening of BOC International demonstrated its
confidence in Hong Kong's future while constituting an actual
support for Hong Kong's position as an international financial
center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falling Dollar Not All Bad News: Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The suffering Australian dollar
has the potential to fall even further but the tumble is not
necessarily a disaster for the Australian economy, economists said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this week the local currency has fallen
almost three U.S. cents and dropped through its record post-float
low to create a new all-time low of 55.30 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press quoted ANZ Banking group chief
economist Saul Eslake as saying that if commodity prices continued
to decline, by another 10 percent for example, the Australian
dollar could sink to anywhere between 54.00 and 52.00 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
But many market participants have commented on the difficulty
on picking a base for the fall of the domestic dollar, simply due
to the fact the currency has not traded in this region before.
</P>
<P>
Before this week the Australian dollar had only traded as low
as 57.10 U.S. cents, which was reached on July 28, 1986.
</P>
<P>
While commenting about the falling dollar, AAP Financial
Markets economist Gary Shilson-Josling said, the Australian dollar
could travel lower from here but market consensus is that it was
undervalued at present levels.
</P>
<P>
"Most people would see the Australian dollar's fair value as
somewhere closer to 60.00 U.S. cents than 55.00," Shilson-Josling
said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overwhelming bearish sentiment on the Australian
dollar economists have been at pains to point out that the fall is
not all bad news for the Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
"If it (the fall) were to become a disorderly rout then it
obviously would be bad news," he said, but at the moment the
tumble is bad news only for people who are planning overseas
holidays or trying to sell imported goods to Australian consumers.
</P>
<P>
The level of the Australian dollar is good for Australia's
exporters, farmers, miners and most of our manufacturers and
therefore for employment.
</P>
<P>
If the Australian dollar fell in such a way or to the point
where the Reserve Bank of Australia felt necessary to raise
interest rates only then would it become a risk to the economy.
</P>
<P>
Many of the economists here believed that it would be unlikely
that the Reserve Bank of Australia would raise official interest
rates to support the currency in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
