<HEADLINE> Natural Disasters Claim 477 Lives in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Devastating disasters, including
floods, mudflows, landslides and hail, have killed some 477
people in southwestern China's Yunnan Province since the beginning
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Gao Zuxing, director of the Yunnan Provincial Civil Affair
Administration, said today that disasters have also injured over
7,000 people and destroyed well over 700,000 houses.
</P>
<P>
He added that disasters have adversely affected over 14 million
people, and have resulted in economic losses of some 5.8 billion
yuan (700 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Gao pointed out the disasters have caused varying levels of
death and damage in 125 of the province's 128 counties.
</P>
<P>
The province has provided adequate shelter, food and medical
treatment for over four million disaster victims. Over four
million soldiers and Yunnan citizens have participated in disaster
relief efforts, with the central government providing some 300
million yuan (36 million dollars) in assistance.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say some parts of Yunnan face the continuing
possibility of similar disasters in the remaining months of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
