<HEADLINE> Russian Commission Urges More Power for Legislature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A tripartite commission of the
Russian government and legislature has drafted an agreement to
urge President Boris Yeltsin to surrender some powers to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The commission, composed of representatives of the government
and both chambers of parliament, also formed a pact on social and
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
Both accords will be presented to the lower house on Friday for
approval, commission coordinator Oleg Morozov said on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to curb the worsening financial situation, Yeltsin
reappointed Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime minister over the weekend
to replace the young Sergei Kiriyenko, who succeeded Chernomyrdin
only five months ago with the support of Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
After the announcement of Chernomyrdin's appointment, the
Communists, who hold a majority in the State Duma (lower house),
demanded more power as a condition for approving the new
appointment.
</P>
<P>
The drafting of the two documents by the commission is a key
step in the State Duma's approval of Chernomyrdin's appointment.
</P>
