<HEADLINE> Clashes Erupt in Hebron as Israel Lifts Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Clashes erupted Friday in the
volatile West Bank city of Hebron between local Palestinians and
Israeli soldiers. Two palestinians were reportedly injured.
</P>
<P>
The clashes occurred shortly after Israeli troops lifted the
week-long military closure on Hebron Friday morning, prompting
hundreds of Palestinian residents to take to the streets to
demonstrate against the closure.
</P>
<P>
A local Palestinian reporter told Xinhua the Palestinian police
tried in vain to control the protesters, who threw stones at
Israeli soldiers guarding the enclaves where Jewish settlers are
living.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers responded with rubber bullets and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
Israel lifted the closure to allow local Palestinians to buy
food and water, but the curfew imposed around the areas where
Jewish settlers are living remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Israel imposed closure on Hebron eight days ago following the
killing of 63-year-old Jewish settler rabbi Shlomo Ra'anan by
suspected Palestinian militants at his home in Tel Rumeida
neighborhood in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
While Israel is only controlling 20 percent of the divided city,
it can impose total closure on the whole city for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The week-long blockade caused great hardship to the local
Palestinians, who suffered from acute shortage of water and food
due to ban on free travel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side estimated that the financial losses of the
closure were about 21 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
