<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Pledges to Devote to Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The new special representative
of the United Nations to Angola, Issa Diallo, said here Friday
that he will devote himself to the peace process in the
war-ravaged country despite all difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Diallo who arrived in Luanda early Friday morning said that he
will devote his "body and soul" to help the Angolan people fully
carry out the 1994 Lusaka Peace accords.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy noted in a statement at the airport that the
faltering Angolan peace process is undergoing the most serious
crisis in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
But Diallo said he believes that the Angolan people will
cherish the hard-won peace and concentrate on the economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The 59-year-old new U.N. envoy also extended his thanks to
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan for his trust.
</P>
<P>
Annan appointed Diallo as the new U.N. envoy to Angola after
Alioune Beye, the late U.N. special representative and Malian
foreign minister died on June 26 when his plane crashed in Cote
d'Ivoire. The investigation of the incident is still going on.
</P>
<P>
Diallo, born in Conakry, capital of Guinea in 1939, was a
graduate from the Department of International Relations and
Political Science in Paris University. He earned his doctorate
degree at the Institute of Advanced International Studies in the
University of Geneva.
</P>
<P>
With 16 years of diplomatic experience, he has a lot of works
on the African politics and economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, Diallo became the special advisor on African affairs
to the then U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar. From
1991 to 1992, he was the acting executive secretary of the U.N.
Commission on African Economy. And then, he had been in charge
of the secretariat of the U.N. agency in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Next Monday, the new U.N. envoy will go to South Africa's
Indian Ocean port of Durban to attend a meeting on Angola of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC)initiated by U.N.
Secretary-General Annan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
