<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Reaches New Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia's battered dollar
suffered another king hit overnight to reach a new record low of
55.30 U.S. cents, prompting a rescue mission by the Reserve Bank
of Australian (RBA).
</P>
<P>
The effects of the central bank intervention, which occurred in
New York with the cooperation of the New York Federal Reserve,
lifted the currency back to around 56 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in New York said the intervention by RBA had come
after the local dollar hit 55.30 U.S. cents, its lowest level
since it was floated in 1983.
</P>
<P>
And as sellers continue to buffet the local dollar, fears
resurfaced that the RBA could still resort to a hike in interest
rates to support the currency.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, Canada and Norway lifted their interest rates to
save their own beleaguered currencies. But traders doubted such a
move would be effective in the current volatile climate.
</P>
<P>
Rory Robertson, senior economist with Bankers Trust, said,
"raising rates to defend currencies in today's circumstances is a
loser's game."
</P>
<P>
"We are clearly in the middle of something over which the RBA
has little control."
</P>
<P>
The offshore sell down followed new drama in Russia, filtering
through to the U.S. sharemarket which sent the Dow Jones
industrial average down 357.4 to 8166.
</P>
<P>
The Australian economy relies heavy upon commodities with fears
any move by Russia to sell its resources at lower prices to pay
off debt would drag down commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
The unfolding drama in Russia and turmoil on markets has seen
the Australian dollar lose almost 3 U.S. cents since the beginning
of the week, or 4.7 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed trading here at 80.27 yen from
82.87 and 1.0058 German marks from 1.0168. 
</P>
</TEXT>
