<HEADLINE> US to Grant Tanzania $90,000 of Medical Supplies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States Friday
donated a batch of medical equipment to the Muhimbili Medical
Center (MMC) which has played a key role in providing medical
treatment to the victims of the August 7 bombing of U.S. embassy
to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Charge de Affaires of the embassy, John Lange, delivered
the assignment of medical supplies such as syringes, dressing
sponge and ventilators to MMC Director General Prof. Samuel
Maselle.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the medical assignment worth 90,000 U.S.
Dollars donated to Tanzania through the U.S. Office of Foreign
Disaster Stance, Lange said, adding that the rest will arrive in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
The charge de affaires expressed his "strong appreciation" for
the quick response of the medical center after the bombing three
weeks ago, which killed 11 people and injured more than 70
others.
</P>
<P>
Most of the wounded have been admitted into the hospital after
the terrorist attack. So far, all patients related to the
incident have been discharged after medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
The medical equipment was carried to Tanzania by the special
plane of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who visited
Dar es Salaam last week to inspect the damaged embassy and
console the victims, Lange said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the progress of investigation into the bomb blast,
Lange declined to comment. He also refused to say how many
Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agents are still in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
However, Dudley O. Sims, the Director of the United States
Information Service (USIS) in Tanzania, revealed that some FBI
agents have already left here.
</P>
<P>
Sims also said that the new U.S. Ambassador to Tanzania Rev.
Charles Stith, 48, the minister of the Union United Methodist
Church in Boston, will come to office in the middle of next
month.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian newspaper The Guardian said Friday that police in
the Mbeya region which borders Zambia, seized seven people of
Arab origin with explosive materials on August 20 and have sent
them to Dar es Salaam for interrogation. 
</P>
