<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and Iran signed an agreement on preventing
double taxation during a recent visit to Beirut by an Iranian
delegation, the London-based Al Hayat Arabic language newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement followed the signing of another deal on
protecting and activating investment in the two countries signed
by Lebanon's Prime Minister Rafik Hariri during a recent visit to
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The two agreements will help boost bilateral relations between
the two countries, said Lebanon's Minister of State for Financial
Affairs Fouad Al Snyora.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A seminar on investment policy of insurance companies
in the Arab world will be held in Cairo on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar is organized by the Arab Insurance
Federation jointly with Egypt's Insurance Association. Insurance
and economic experts said the meeting would discuss the role of
the insurance companies in state economic policy in view of the
world changes that affect the insurance investment policy.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's foreign trade grew by 1.5 billion Egyptian
pounds (438 million U.S. dollars) in the first four months this
year to 19.2 billion pounds (5.6 billion dollars), the latest
edition of the Middle East News reported.
</P>
<P>
This figure was compared to 17.7 billion pounds (5.2 billion
dollars) in the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, imports increased to 16 billion pounds (4.7
billion dollars) from 13.4 billion (3.9 billion dollars) in the
same period last year, while exports dwindled to 3.1 billion
pounds (906 million dollars) from 4.2 billion pounds (1.2 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Six states and regions have ordered 15,026 quintals of
Egyptian cotton before announcing the cotton export price due next
Sunday, the Egyptian daily Al Ahram reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
These states included Brazil, Germany, India, Taiwan, Turkey
and the U.S., it said. Egypt's last season's cotton exports
reached 1.5 million quintals valued at 187 million dollars.
</P>
