<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Economy Declines in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A crude initial assessment
suggested that the gross domestic product (GDP) of Hong Kong could
have fallen by around 5 percent in the second quarter of 1998 over
a year earlier, the government announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
In light of the lackluster performance so far, the government
forecasts that GDP for the whole year will contract by around 4
percent in real terms, compared with a 5.3 percent increase
recorded for last year.
</P>
<P>
The enormous drop for this year reflected largely the slowdown
in economic activities and the negative external factors following
the financial crisis in the region as a whole, financial secretary
Donald Tsang told a press conference Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The figure of negative 4 percent compared with the average of
negative 3 percent suggested by eight reputable forecasters of
Hong Kong's economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
But Hong Kong economy has been adjusting very speedily to
uphold competitiveness, with wages softening, asset prices falling
substantially and inflation at its lowest level since 1986, said
the financial official.
</P>
<P>
"The adjustment process is very fast and efficient," Tsang
noted.
</P>
<P>
As a free and open economy, Hong Kong cannot be left unscathed
when an unprecedented financial turmoil swept the region, said
Hong Kong's top financial official.
</P>
<P>
Tsang noted that a recovery can only be seen when the Japanese
economy improves and the yen stabilizes, and the turbulent Russian
financial market calms down.
</P>
<P>
Government Economist K Y Tang explained the second quarter
figure at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
A further slackening in both exports and local consumer demand
led to a negative 5 percent GDP growth in the second quarter,
which represented a further slow down from the 2.8 percent decline
recorded for the first quarter, Tang pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's exports of goods slowed down further in the
quarter, with exports to those regional economies hit by the
financial turmoil falling markedly further, while exports of
services declined further along with the weakness in inbound
tourism, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
On the same time, he said, local consumer sentiment was hit by
the slackened income, increased unemployment, and the further
decline in asset prices.
</P>
<P>
He agreed with Tsang that, with the economic adjusting
efficiently, the cost of living and the cost of doing business in
Hong Kong have both moderated, enabling the city to uphold its
competitiveness in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
