<HEADLINE> S. African Vigilante Group Denies Links to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A vigilante group in Cape
Town, South Africa, Friday denied that it is linked to the August
25 bombing in a U.S.-franchised restaurant following the arrest
of a member of the group.
</P>
<P>
The People Against Gangsterism and Drugs (Pagad) group said
that it dissociated itself from the bomb attack. It also sharply
criticized the police's handling of the investigation of the
case.
</P>
<P>
"The police must act in a serious and responsible way and not
just confine their investigation to a suspicion that Pagad was
somehow involved in the bomb attack," Pagad spokesman Cassiem
Parker said.
</P>
<P>
A man and two women were detained in the departure hall of
Cape Town International Airport Thursday afternoon as they were
about to board an Egyptian flight to Cairo. Police have
reportedly questioned them in connection with the Cape blast.
</P>
<P>
One person was killed and 27 others were injured in the
bombing, including some children.
</P>
<P>
But police denied that they arrested the three for
investigation of the bombing, saying that there were
discrepancies in the travel documents of the three and the
detention was carried out under the Aliens Control Act.
</P>
<P>
Pagad accused the police of conducting a witch-hunt against
the organization.
</P>
<P>
Police has been investigating a link between the restaurant
bombing and other blasts in Cape Town in recent months, in which
many people were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
Numerous pipe bombs have exploded at the homes of gangsters
and drug lords in on-going skirmishes between the alleged drug
pedlars and Pagad. There are rumors that Pagad is linked to
Muslim extremists and has an anti-U.S. agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
