<HEADLINE> Singapore Stocks Fall Through Key 900-Point Support Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Share prices took fresh
hammering on the Singapore Stock Market Friday as the benchmark
Straits Times Industrial Index (STII) dropped and punctured
through its key support level of 900 points following the Wall
Street plunge and the worsening crisis in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The STII lost 25.62 points to close at 885.26 points, the lowest
level in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Friday is the last day when the 30 year-old STII was used as a
market barometer and a revamped Straits Times Index (STI) will
take the place on August 31.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market fell on the back of a weaker Wall
Street and concerns over Russia's economy.
</P>
<P>
The market was driven mostly by sentiment with fundamentals
having little influence, they added.
</P>
<P>
They also said activities were fueled by speculation over the
composition of the revamped STI index.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover increased to 180.74 million units valued at
293.68 million Singapore dollars (about 165.92 million U.S.
dollars). Losers outstripped gainers by 224 to 61 with 304
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
ST Engg was the most active stock of the day as it registered a
 turnover of 17.63 million units. It was followed by SingTel that
had 15.31 million stocks traded. M Res was next with 12.33
million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SIA 200 was the top gainer of the day as it gained 30 cents to
end at 5.40 Singapore dollars. SIA F edged up 15 cents to finish
at 7.70 Singapore dollars. NatElec inched up eight cents to close
at 3.56 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Transmarco was the biggest loser of the day as
it dropped by 4.19 Singapore dollars to close at 1.91. Creative 50
shed 80 cents to finish at 18.20 Singapore dollars. Thai Pr moved
down by 70 cents to close at 2.00 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
