<HEADLINE> Pak PM Calls for Iranian Coordination on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Friday called on Iran to "closely coordinate" its policies
with Pakistan on the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
He was talking to Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Mohsin
Ameenzadeh who arrived here earlier Friday with a message from
Iranian President Seyed Mohammad Khatami, said an official press
release.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister underlined "the need for Pakistan and Iran
to closely coordinate their policies at this important juncture."
</P>
<P>
He voiced deep concern about the missing Iranian personnel in
Afghanistan and assured the Iranian guest Pakistan's fullest
cooperation in helping to locate them.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the close, historical Pakistan-Iran relations
based on religious and cultural affinities, Sharif stressed the
need for closer contact at the leadership level between the two
old allies with a view to strengthening their ties.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official will also hold formal talks with Foreign
Minister Sartaj Aziz on important regional issues late in the day.
</P>
<P>
His one-day trip here follows the recent visit to Iran by
Pakistani State Minister for Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju.
</P>
<P>
Tension emerged between Pakistan and Iran since 11 Iranian
nationals have been missing in northern Afghanistan when the
Islamic Taliban captured Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of
anti-Taliban alliance, early this month.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan recognizes the Taliban regime while Iran accepts the
northern alliance led by former Afghan president Burhannuddin
Rabbani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
