<HEADLINE> Australian Current Account Deficit Narrows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia's current account
deficit narrowed in the second quarter of this year after a boost
to both exports and imports, according to the latest official
figures released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said the current
account deficit fell by 801 million Australian dollars (440
million U.S. dollars), or 11 percent, over the previous quarter to
a seasonally adjusted 6.518 billion Australian dollars (3.584
billion U.S. dollars) for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said the result followed higher non-rural exports,
although this was partly offset by higher capital goods imports.
</P>
<P>
The ABS said exports of goods and services rose by 4.9 percent
to a seasonally adjusted 29.143 billion Australian dollars (about
16 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports were up 2.6 percent for the second quarter
to be worth 30.934 billion Australian dollars (about 17 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"In seasonally adjusted terms, the deficit on goods and
services at current prices was 1.79 billion Australian dollars
(984 million U.S. dollars), down by 560 million Australian dollars
(308 million U.S. dollars) in the June quarter 1998."
</P>
<P>
The bureau also said Australia's net foreign debt fell 1
percent to 222 billion Australian dollars (about 122 billion U.S.
dollars) by the end of the second quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
