<HEADLINE> Mandela Assures Safety of Athletics Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela moved swiftly on Thursday to allay fears over the
safety of participants in the forthcoming athletics World Cup in
the country following Tuesday's fatal bombing.
</P>
<P>
Many of the world's leading track and field stars will gather
at the Johannesburg Stadium for the eighth International Amateur
Athletics Federation (IAAF) World Cup in Athletics, a quadrennial
showpiece, from September 11-13.
</P>
<P>
A bomb exploded Tuesday night at a U.S.-franchised restaurant
in Cape Town, killing one person and injuring 27 others,
including international tourists.
</P>
<P>
Police suspect the blast is linked to anti-U.S. Muslim
extremists, who might intend to retaliate against U.S. missile
strikes at Sudan and Afghanistan last week.
</P>
<P>
The president's guarantees of safety came hot on the heels of
a report that U.S. athletics authorities were considering
withdrawing their team amid concerns for the safety of their
athletes.
</P>
<P>
"The South African security forces are equal to the task of
ensuring the safety of all participants in the World Cup," a
presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to World Cup media liaison officer Chris Day, the
U.S. team management is due to meet today over the issue.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the local organizing committee of the World
Cup had already sent a report to U.S. officials guaranteeing them
the safety of their athletes.
</P>
<P>
"The report was commissioned after discussions at the highest
level," he said, referring to meetings with Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was also announced that the eight men's and
women's teams would be competing for the Nelson Mandela Trophy
during the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Trophies bearing the president's name would also be presented
at all future World Cup events, the IAAF said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The body said the continental team event emphasizes team
rather than individual and therefore places special focus on
unity. Mandela is the one person in the world who best
personifies the quest for unity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
