<HEADLINE> Tibetans Poised to Combat New Flood Crest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The People's Liberation Army (PLA)
troops stationed in southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region and
local Tibetan residents are poised to fight another flood crest
that is expected to arrive before September 10.
</P>
<P>
Lingering rainfall since mid-August has raised water levels in
Tibet's major rivers, including the Yarlung Zangbo River, and in
some places flood waters have submerged large farming areas
and damaged many houses over the several past weeks.
</P>
<P>
The joint efforts of some 100,000 local residents and PLA men
have greatly alleviated the flood situation and successfully
evacuated many flood victims, holding economic losses to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
However, meteorologists recently forecast that another round of
torrential rains affecting a large part of the autonomous region
is expected soon.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regional government has thus allocated one
million yuan (120,000 US dollars) as emergency flood-fighting
funds, which will be used to repair potentially dangerous
embankments, reinforce old dikes, and fund the flood-fighting
patrolling troops who are working around the clock.
</P>
<P>
A senior engineer with the autonomous regional meteorological
department warned that although water levels in Tibet's major
rivers began to fall at 8:00 a.m. today, the new round of rainfall
will once again raise water levels which are still near the danger
line, and as a result flood-fighters across the autonomous region
should remain alert.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
