<HEADLINE> Islamization, Right Step for Pakistan: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif on Friday said the introduction of Islamization in the
society is "the right step for the nation," adding that it will
not violate anyone's rights.
</P>
<P>
The 15th Constitutional Amendment Bill to make Quran and Sunnah
the supreme law in the country "will not violate anyone's rights
-- there should be no doubt on that count," Sharif told reporters
at the Parliament House.
</P>
<P>
He assured that an in-depth democratic debate will take place
on the bill "which is aimed at bringing about social justice and
welfare of the people."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the bill will be passed with
consensus by the two houses of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The bill provides for safeguarding the rights of the
minorities, and our friendship with other countries will continue,
we will have good international relations," he said in response to
a question about the reaction of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, the prime minister announced in a live
television address to the nation that the 15th amendment is being
introduced in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said that the decision would change the social fabric of the
society, and lay a solid foundation for eliminating crime,
corruption and malpractice -- which have crept into the society
like "a rampant cancer."
</P>
<P>
A two-third majority in the Senate and the National Assembly is
required to pass the amendment. The government will get it passed
in the National Assembly easily, but face pressure in the Senate
as it does not enjoy a majority there.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to Islamize the society in Pakistan had been made by
late president Zia-ul-Haq. Opponents to Haq termed his attempts to
Islamize the society as cynical and politically motivated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
