<HEADLINE> Nigeria, S. Africa to Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and South Africa soon
will sign a bilateral trade and cooperation agreement to enhance
the improved relations between the two countries following the
recent visit to South Africa by the Nigerian head of state.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will cover various areas including avoidance of
double taxation, protection of investment, science and
technology, and protection of fiscal evasion, Nigeria's state
news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two countries were frozen following
the controversial execution of Ken Saro Wiwa and eight other
human rights activists in 1995 by the Nigerian government of the
late military leader Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The total trade between Nigeria and South Africa increased
from less than two million Naira (about 23,000 U.S. Dollars) in
1992 to 57 million Naira (about 678,000 U.S. Dollars) last year,
according to the figures released by the South African trade
organization. 
</P>
