<HEADLINE> Students Across Australia Rally Against Racism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- About 8,000 students and young
people across Australia rallied Friday against racism, condemning
the Australian federal government for its failure to combat
racism.
</P>
<P>
The national rally was staged in 14 cities, including all of
Australia's eight capital cities, such as Sydney, Canberra,
Brisbane, Melbourne, Hobart, Adelaide, Perth, Darwin, Newcastle
and Wollongong.
</P>
<P>
The national rally was organized by Resistance, a socialist
youth group in Australia. The group launched its campaign against
racism and anti-Asian immigration politician Pauline Hanson with
protests on July 24 and 28, when more than 14,000 students were
estimated to have walked out of school to attend rallies.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 students marched through Sydney Friday afternoon
demanding an end to what they called racist government policies.
</P>
<P>
Students burnt posters of Pauline Hanson as they marched from
Hyde Park, past State Parliament and on to Australian Prime
Minister John Howard's office in Phillip Street.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Deputy Mayor Henry Tsang addressed the students at Hyde
Park and urged them not to clash with police.
</P>
<P>
Ryan Liddell of Resistance, the rally's coordinator, said,
"It's not just Hanson and her One Nation Party that are racist,
it's also the very government of Australia itself."
</P>
<P>
About 500 students took to the streets in Melbourne Friday as
part of the national rally, the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 250 students marched through central Brisbane,
Australia's third largest city, in a protest against racism.
</P>
<P>
In Adelaide, capital city of the state of South Australia,
labor union representatives joined 350 high school students to
rally against the perceived racism of Pauline Hanson's One Nation
party and the federal government.
</P>
<P>
Resistance member and rally organizer Arrow Tong said the
protest was needed because the federal government has failed to
make any effort to combat the racist views spread by Hanson.
</P>
<P>
"People are waking up and realizing the government is not going
to do anything to fight racism unless we ask them to," Tong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
