<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Claims Three Lives In Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 6.6 on
the Richter scale killed three people and injured six others in
the western part of the northwestern Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region Thursday afternoon, according to China's earthquake
monitoring service.
</P>
<P>
The quake occurred at 5:03 p.m. local time in Jiashi County,
where three people were injured, 3,652 room units collapsed and
another 18,771 rooms were seriously damaged.
</P>
<P>
Jiashi's 13 counties were affected by the earthquake, and in
Shule County, three people died and three others were injured.
</P>
<P>
Tremors were felt in Kashi Prefecture and the Kizilsu Kirgis
Autonomous Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
By 10:00 a.m. today, there had been a total of 227 aftershocks
larger than 2.0 on the Richter scale, and three were stronger than
5.0.
</P>
<P>
Chinese seismologists say these earthquakes were part of an
earthquake group that began on January 21 and has included nine
quakes stronger than 6.0 on the Richter scale, the longest and
strongest quake group in China since seismological records have
been kept.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
