<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 10:00 GMT August 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair Friday urged the
Russian government to stick to its reform program in an effort to
take the country out of the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Russian financial situation continues worsening with the
Russian rouble going into a free-fall triggered by Russian Central
Bank's suspension of all foreign exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
Blair said in a BBC Radio interview Friday morning: "It is a
very serious situation in Russia, there's no doubt about that at
all. The only answer and response to it is to carry on with the
process of reforms." (UK-Blair-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's Central Bank decided on Friday to continue
the suspension of all foreign currency trading on the country's
main exchange, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken in accordance with the authorization the
Central Bank granted to the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange
(MICEX). It is the third successive day that foreign currency
trade has been suspended on MICEX.
</P>
<P>
The authorization allows a halt of trading if there is a major
disproportion between the offer and the demand at the currency
exchange, the press said. (Russia-Currency)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Ugandan army will remain deep in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) unless President Laurent Kabila accepts a
political solution to the crisis there, a Ugandan general said.
</P>
<P>
Major General Salim Saleh, President Yoweri Museveni's brother
and senior presidential advisor on defense and security, made the
remarks in Uganda's northern district of Gulu Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's leading daily newspaper New Vision Friday quoted Saleh
as saying there is a sizable Ugandan military presence in the DRC,
but he did not elaborate. (Uganda-DR Congo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Another five large Russian banks led by the National
Reserve Bank (NRB) have merged into a new group, the Itar-Tass
news agency reported on Friday. (Russia-Banks-Merge)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnamese President Tran Duc Luong signed an amnesty
Friday to release 5,219 prisoners before the September 2 national
day.
</P>
<P>
Complete amnesty was granted to 5,166 inmates, with another 53
being effectively being paroled. Anyone who seeks to emigrate will
receive due consideration, Nguyen Canh Dinh, director of the
president's office told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the amnesty, Dinh said, inmates must have served
at least one-third of their sentence, or 12 years for a life
sentence. (Vietnam-Amnesty) 
</P>
</TEXT>
