<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Release 5,219 Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese President Tran Duc
Luong signed an amnesty Friday to release 5,219 prisoners before
the September 2 national day.
</P>
<P>
Complete amnesty was granted to 5,166 inmates, with another 53
being effectively being paroled. Anyone who seeks to emigrate will
receive due consideration, Nguyen Canh Dinh, director of the
president's office told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the amnesty, Dinh said, inmates must have served
at least one-third of their sentence, or 12 years for a life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
"With the noble humanitarian tradition of the nation and the
humanitarian nature of the Vietnamese laws, a special amnesty is
made without discrimination against any inmates and regardless of
what crimes they have committed and who they are, Vietnamese or
foreigners, " he said. "All those who meet the conditions may be
pardoned."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam had announced three other amnesties this decade,
respectively in 1990, 1993 and 1995. But the number of the
prisoners affected this time is much larger, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
