<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Emerges as China's Bordeaux for Wine Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region in northwest China is rapidly emergering as one of the
country's leading wine producers.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia's soil and climate conditions purportedly equal those
in Bordeaux, a region in southwest France famous for its high
quality grapes.
</P>
<P>
Years of research and comparative studies have led Chinese wine
experts to conclude that some 80,000 hectares of fertile land east
of the Helan Mountains provide great potential for the area to
become one of the world's best grape and wine production regions.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that loose soil featuring a high content of
organic matter, combined with over 3,000 hours of sunshine
annually, sharp disparities between day and night temperatures, a
dry climate and adequate irrigation, makes the region and ideal
location for vineyards.
</P>
<P>
The experts conducted an in-depth fact-finding visit to
Bordeaux in 1994 and concluded that the Ningxia region surpasses
the French region in terms of temperature and humidity.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has attached great importance to
related research, and is currently planting a 2,660-hectare
vineyard and constructing a winery with a designed annual capacity
of 40,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture also plans to establish vineyards
and wineries in Ningxia, home to the Hui ethnic minority
nationality.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia has already established a 200-hectare vineyard and a
modern winery producing highly popular "Xixia" (Western Xia) red
and dry wines. The region currently depends totally on grape
imports from France.
</P>
<P>
A number of leading Chinese winemakers, including those
producing Great Wall and Dynasty, have increased purchases of
grape juice from Ningxia, and the region is currently engaged in
talks concerning transfers of wine production technology from
France.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 13 in Landslides, Flooding in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen people were killed and
four others were missing as landslides and flooding triggered by
torrential rains lashed Japan Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the thirteen victims died in Fukushima Prefecture,
northeastern Japan, on Thursday, including five who were trapped
in a welfare facility, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The disaster also resulted in death in neighboring Tochigi
Prefecture and Nara Prefecture, western Japan.
</P>
<P>
Train services were disrupted due to the heavy rain, railway
officials said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4,053 buildings in 13 prefectures were flooded, the
Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rains were caused by the season's fourth typhoon, now
in waters off the Ogasawara Islands in the Pacific, some 1,000
kilometers south of Tokyo, the agency said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0164 </DOCNO>
