<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army to Remain Deep in DR Congo: General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan army will remain deep
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) unless President
Laurent Kabila accepts a political solution to the crisis there,
a Ugandan general said.
</P>
<P>
Major General Salim Saleh, President Yoweri Museveni's brother
and senior presidential advisor on defense and security, made the
remarks in Uganda's northern district of Gulu Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's leading daily newspaper New Vision Friday quoted
Saleh as saying there is a sizable Ugandan military presence in
the DRC, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said that Uganda is being attacked by the DRC, Zimbabwe
and Angola and therefore Ugandan army should be in the central
African country to protect its national interests.
</P>
<P>
There is evidence that Kabila is arranging to attack us from
all frontiers and we have to defend ourselves, he added.
</P>
<P>
The call for cease-fire made at the summit of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) over the weekend should be
accepted and observed by both warring parties in the DRC, Saleh
asserted.
</P>
<P>
Since August 2 when war erupted in Kinshasa, Kabila has
accused Uganda of being behind the rebels and demanded Ugandan
troops to withdraw from his country.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Ugandan First Deputy Prime Minister and Minister
of Foreign Affairs Eriya Kategaya told Parliament that Ugandan
troops are in the DRC, not to support the rebels there but to
protect the national interests of Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
