<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tea Production Drops in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tea production was down
by more than 50 percent in the last two months, according to Kenya
Tea Development Authority (KTDA).
</P>
<P>
"With the cold season, production has fallen drastically,
sometimes as low as 60 percent," said a senior official at KTDA.
</P>
<P>
Tea yield had dwindled to 5,000 kilograms a day in some
factories, whose intake is in the average of 100,000 kilograms
during normal seasons.
</P>
<P>
Tea does well during wet seasons coupled with sunny weather
earlier this year, but the country, one of the world's leading
tea exporters, has experienced cold weather during the past three
months.
</P>
<P>
KTDA had predicted higher yields this year thanks to the El
Nino-related rains, expecting that tea output could reach 600
million kilograms compared to 520 million kilograms last year.
</P>
<P>
But the current cold weather may affect yields and production
of tea, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, KTDA is pursuing the registration of a farmers'
bank before the end of this year in line with a resolution made
during the annual growers' meeting held on July 30.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, more than 500 representatives endorsed a
proposal to start National Tea Growers' Bank to serve the
interests of small-scale farmers.
</P>
<P>
Growers complained that commercial banks continued to reap
billions of Shillings every year from the framing community but
little had been done to avail affordable credit for the promotion
of agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
