<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Zhu Rongji Addresses Religious Issues (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
reaffirmed here Wednesday that China practices freedom of
religious belief and noted that the nation's population of over
1.2 billion people includes of 100 million religious followers.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhu said, neither the proportion or influence of
religion in China equals that in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the remarks while meeting with visiting Pat
Robertson, chairman of the Board of the Christian Broadcast
Network, and his party.
</P>
<P>
He said Robertson's China tour will help to enhance mutual
understanding between the American and Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Zhu went on to say that a large number of Chinese have
followed Confucianism, Buddhism and Taoism over the past 2,000
years.
</P>
<P>
Confucianism is based on traditional concepts, morality and
philosophy, rather than on religion, Zhu said, adding that
Buddhism was introduced to China over 2,000 years ago and Taoism
originated in the country.
</P>
<P>
Zhu pointed out that Catholicism arrived in China in 1582 and
Christianity in 1807. He noted the history of both faithes in
China is thus comparatively short.
</P>
<P>
He said the nation has consistently pursued a policy of freedom
of religion since the founding of the the People's Republic of
China in 1949, and has clearly stipulated the policy in the
Chinese Constitution.
</P>
<P>
While some shortcomings might arise in China's practices
concerning unlawful activities conducted under the pretext of
religion, the Chinese government nonetheless fully respects and
protects religious freedom, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, "I recently heard a report which
indicated that the number of lamaseries established in Tibet over
the past two decades has surpassed any period in history". Even
more importantly, the new lamaseries were established with funds
provided by the central government, rather than with donations
from the faithful, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
"We have historically recognized the role of religion in social
development. Those who believe in religion and atheists alike
believe that people should enjoy spiritual strength", the premier
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
