<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Zhu Rongji Addresses Religious Issues (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese Premier said that China's economic growth could
reach the set goal of 8 percent in 1998, though the country's GDP
in the first half of the year grew by only 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's economy has stood the test of the Asian
financial crisis, and he reiterated that the Chinese currency will
not be devalued.
</P>
<P>
Zhu explained that the financial crisis in Asia which has
resulted in the deterioration of the international financial
environment has had a great impact on China's exports.
</P>
<P>
However, China has adopted measures to expand domestic demand
with a positive financial policy, and has enlarged the scale of
infrastructure construction to gear up for economic growth, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
China is confident of arriving at the economic goal of 8 percent
growth for 1998 as a whole through efforts in the latter half of
the year, Zhu told Robertson.
</P>
<P>
China's has achieved a quite favorable balance of trade in
recent years, Zhu continued, noting that with China's investment
environment much improved, direct foreign investment of 30
to 40 billion U.S. dollars flows into the country every year.
</P>
<P>
China's international income and expenses are basically balanced
and the country has experienced a sound financial market
with sufficient foreign currency reserves, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China has not devalued its currency in the face
of the Asian financial crisis has contributed greatly to Asia, and
to the world as a whole, Zhu said, emphasizing that the Asian
financial crisis will not have much influence on China's economic
development and reform process.
</P>
<P>
China's reform goal is to establish a socialist market economy,
which differs from that of other countries, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The difference between China's socialist market economy and the
capitalist market economy in the U.S. is that China insists on the
joint development of multi-formed ownership with public ownership
as the mainstay, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"We don't think public-owned enterprises must be worse than
privately owned ones. In fact, public-owned enterprises can be
managed very well," Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
The makeup of public ownership can actually be diversified, and
not limited only to the form of state ownership, Zhu elaborated,
noting that a diversified public ownership and the joint
development of multi-formed economic entities has in fact taken
shape in China.
</P>
<P>
The ownership of China's enterprises now has three
forms: state-owned, which generally accounts for 35 percent,
collectively owned, or firms under the cooperative system, which
is also a form of public ownership, accounts for another 35
percent, and the final 30 percent which is privately owned
including the overseas-funded firms, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Although the state-owned firms only account for one-third of
the total, they dominate the country's economy by providing 85
percent of China's tax revenue, Zhu noted, saying that China is
not privatizing the state-owned firms, but instead is gradually
changing them into shareholding enterprises, with the majority of
shares held by the state.
</P>
<P>
"This conforms to the situation in China", Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also briefed the delegation on China's fight against heavy
flooding.
</P>
<P>
Robertson expressed admiration for the enormous progress in
China's economic development and his concern and sympathy for the
people in the flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is visiting China at the invitation of China's
State Bureau of Religious Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Army Command, Staff College Opened in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's first Army Command
and Staff College (ACSC) was opened Friday by President Chandrika
Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
It is located at Sapugaskanda in the Northern suburb of
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
According to the ACSC Commandant Major General Anton Wijendra,
the objective of the college is to prepare selected officers for
the positions of majors and lieutenant colonels in command and on
the staff.
</P>
<P>
He said they hoped to expand the college to accommodate 50
officers by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Wijendra explained that it costs the state 14,000 U.S. dollars
to send an officer for training at an overseas staff college. The
need for professional officers in the field has been acutely felt
as an average of only about four officers get the opportunity to
attend overseas command and staff colleges annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
