<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nikkei Index Nosedives to Lowest Level in 12 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged for the third
consecutive trading day Friday with the key Nikkei index closing at
its lowest level in more than 12 years.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange tumbled 498.16 points, or 3.46
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 13,915.63, th lowest close
since March 7, 1986, when it marked 13,994.63.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, also dropped to its lowest close in 12 years,
falling 29.98 points or 2.68 percent to 1,086.99.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 550 million
shares from Thursday's 505.63 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei, which fell 3.04 percent Thursday, was destined for
another steep drop after the Dow Jones Industrial Average in New York
sank 4.3 percent overnight and major indexes in Europe posted similar
declines.
</P>
<P>
with Russia's political leadership in doubt, Japan's economy still
in recession, and fears of a worldwide price deflation strong, traders
were reluctant to say whether a strong rebound was near.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of issues, from big-name companies to little-known firms,
retreated to record lows, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,333 issues listed on the First Section, losers surpassed
gainers 1,095 to 133, with 75 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
