<HEADLINE> Poland's Financial Market Hit by Russian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski called for calm on Thursday as the country's financial
market was rocked by the Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
WIG, the main index of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, dropped by
6.1 percent to 13,001.4 point on Thursday, while the Polish zloty
fell 0.32 percent against the U.S. dollar following a 1.9 percent
decline on Wednesday, reported the Polish Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts pointed out that the turmoil was caused chiefly
by the poor performance of Polish enterprises, coupled with the
negative impact of the Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Poland's massive privatization program, scheduled to be carried
out this year and next year, may be indefinitely delayed, said
some financial experts.
</P>
<P>
They also predicted that the turmoil will also slow the pace of
the development of Poland's stock market.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski told a press conference on Thursday that the impact
of the Russian crisis is serious, but not destructive.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Polish people to stick to the reform policy,
observe the financial regulations and boost exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
