<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian Currency Tumbles Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Malawian currency has hit
new low within four days to 42 Kwacha to one U.S. Dollar,
according to the Malawian central bank.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Malawi attributed the currency's
depreciation to a number of factors which include an 80 million
U.S. Dollar drop in the 1998 proceeds from tobacco exports.
</P>
<P>
But the central bank said that the situation would not
degenerate and would be stabilized soon.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday the currency dropped from 27 Kwacha to one U.S.
Dollar to 34 Kwacha to the dollar amidst hopes that it would
stabilize at that level.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the value of the South African Rand and the
Zimbabwean Dollar is also to blame because the two countries are
among Malawi's major trading partners.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Malawian government's last budget deficit of 600
million Kwacha (22 million U.S. Dollars) coupled with poor fiscal
policies have helped to worsen matters, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Malawi would like to assure the public
Tuesday that a further fall of such magnitude was unlikely to
recur in the near future.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said that unless Malawi had enough foreign
exchange coming into the country in the form of export sales and
foreign aid, it would be hard to stabilize the Kwacha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
