<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Sharemarket Tumbles as Investors Scared off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand sharemarket
dived to a five-year low Friday after investors were spooked by
big falls in sharemarkets overseas as a result of the current
Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 3.3 percent or 63
points to 1848, copying falls in sharemarkets in New York, Tokyo
and Hong Kong, the TV Zealand reported.
</P>
<P>
On the New Zealand sharemarket, there were 94 falls and only 2
rises among the stocks traded.
</P>
<P>
One major stock hit hard was insurance giant AMP, which fell
154 cents in two days to 2351 cents. Brierley Investments lost 4
cents to 67 cents.
</P>
<P>
Commodity stocks were also suffering, with Fletcher Paper down
14 cents to 130 cents, and Carter Holt losing 13 cents to 154
cents.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post, a Wellington-based newspaper, quoted
sharebroker Raif Goodwin of Merrill Lynch as saying that the
market fall was "driven entirely by external events".
</P>
<P>
"The decline on our equities market correlates with what is
happening in offshore markets," he said, adding that the slump was
hitting stocks across the board.
</P>
<P>
Further falls in New Zealand sharemarket are likely, he
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Brendan O'Donovan, chief economist of the New Zealand National
Bank, was quoted by the paper as saying that the turbulence in
Russia has spilled into financial markets globally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
