<HEADLINE> Shark May Help Heal Wounds: NZ Researchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Shark cartilage, already
widely
promoted as a cancer treatment, may speed up wound recovery, the
Evening
Post quoted Wellington School of Medicine researchers as saying
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper reported that the researchers
led by Dr
Paul Davis have isolated a compound in shark cartilage that
encourages
growth of new blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the compound has been isolated and a
provisional
patent taken out, the paper quoted Dr Davis as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier research showed shark cartilage also contained an
ingredient
that could help prevent the growth of new blood vessels essential
to
cancer tumors.
</P>
<P>
Experiments are being carried out to see if shark cartilage can
reduce
haemangiomas or "strawberry marks" which afflict some children, Dr
Davis
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
