<HEADLINE> Landslides Cause Devastation in India's Hills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The recent massive landslides
in India's Uttar Pradesh hills have caused devastation, claiming
350 lives so far in two districts and damaging property worth tens
of millions of U.S. dollars, official sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The main cause of the landslides, the worst recorded in the
northern Indian state, was the result of blunt deforestation and
rapid development of the region, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
On the nights of August 18-19, the Malpa village and Ukhimuth
township experienced massive rains followed by heavy landslides,
which have virtually washed away the entire village, where at
least 60 pilgrims were camping.
</P>
<P>
The death toll was around 200 in the village excluding the 60
pilgrims. The army, paramilitary forces and the Indian Air Force
with the help of local police have recovered only 32 bodies.
</P>
<P>
A search is going on for the rest of the bodies but reports
said it is almost impossible to recover more bodies because most
of them are buried under 21 meter high muddy debris.
</P>
<P>
The death toll in Ukhimuth might be about 125, but only 32
bodies have been recovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Sets Up Body to Monitor Coastal Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has set
up a multi-disciplinary monitoring body to check coastal
pollution, official sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The body will assess the pollution load, identify the sources
and take up remedial measures against the pollution.
</P>
<P>
Certain coastal areas have been identified as "areas of
concern" and will be given priority. Ports in general have been
considered as one of the main culprits in pollution.
</P>
<P>
The Ocean Department has sponsored a plan of action on coastal
ocean monitoring and a prediction system. Guidelines are being
framed for the ports to follow them to regulate their discharge of
solid and liquid wastes into the sea, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the coastal-based industries discharging their
wastes which directly or indirectly enter the sea, municipalities
and other civic bodies also are answerable in this regard. Each of
the polluting sources, particularly those located in the "areas of
concern," are liable to prosecution if they discharge the
untreated wastes or effluents directly or indirectly into the sea
or stretches thereof.
</P>
<P>
The pollutants include diverse industrial wastes such as
synthetic organic chemicals, metals and radioactive materials,
petroleum hydrocarbons, sewage and litters. The discharges badly
affect the marine life and other living resources.
</P>
<P>
Activities at 11 large, 16 medium-sized and 78 small ports and
the spills left from oil imports have added to the problems along
the coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
