<HEADLINE> All 18 Aboard Crashed Plane in Nepal Die </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 28 (Xinhua) -- All the 18 people aboard a
plane that crashed a week ago were found dead, Radio Nepal said
Friday, quoting rescuers.
</P>
<P>
It said that except the two bodies of women, the rest could not
be identified as they are "completely burnt and scattered."
</P>
<P>
Rescuers on Thursday reached the crash site at an altitude of
12,000 feet (some 4,000 meters), the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated Twin Otter aircraft lost contact five minutes
after taking off last Friday in Jomsom, western Nepal. It was
scheduled to fly in 20 minutes to Pokhara, 80 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday morning, it was found crashed to pieces about 13
kilometers southwest of Mt. Annapurna. Those aboard include three
crew members and three Indians.
</P>
<P>
A five-member government team Thursday began investigation into
the accident.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21 air disasters had taken place in Nepal since
1975.
</P>
<P>
In July 1991, a Twin Otter plane of the army crashed, killing
three aboard.
</P>
<P>
In July and September 1992, a Thai airbus and a Pakistani
airbus crashed in Nepal respectively, killing a total of 280
people.
</P>
<P>
In July 1993, an aircraft on a domestic flight crashed, killing
all 18 on board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
