<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 27 (Xinhua) -- When it comes to settling debts
between Russia's gas companies and Ukraine's machine industry,
Ukraine is insisting on balancing the accounts, Ukrainian Prime
Minister Valery Pustovoitenko said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told a press conference the method of debt
payment is one of the main issues under discussion with his
Russian counterpart Viktor Chernomyrdin. (Ukraine-Russia-Debts)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- Hungary's Finance Minister Jarai Zsigmond said on
Thursday that the Russian financial crisis had brought only slight
impact to his country.
</P>
<P>
He told a news conference that Hungary's exports to Russia
accounted for only 4 percent of its total, while 70 percent went
to European Union countries. (Hungary-Finance)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- Nestle-Sofia's main objective is to become the main
chocolate and confectionary producer among Central European Free
Trade Agreement member states, the company's Director General
Mitris Koronakis said at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nestle-Sofia, a subsidiary of the Swiss Nestle company, is
marketing 7 to 12 percent of its output in the former Soviet
Republics, Hungary and South Africa. The percentage is expected to
increase to 20 percent soon. (Nestle-Sofia)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
Thursday as the global financial markets were affected by Russian
and Asian economic crises.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 142.18 yen,
down from 144.02 late Wednesday. It also was trading at 1.7941
marks, down from 1.8061 marks, and 1.5788 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.5677. (NY-Dollar Falling)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Dow industrials plunged 357 points Thursday,
its third-biggest point loss ever and the biggest percentage drop
since last October's tumbling. (NY-Stocks-Down) 
</P>
