<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Adopts Lockerbie Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The 15 members of the
United Nations Security Council voted Thursday to adopt a draft
resolution offered by the United States and Britain to change the
venue for the Lockerbie trial.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, unanimously adopted by the council following
two days of informal consultations, endorsed the U.S.-UK plan to
try the two suspected Libyans in the Netherlands under Scottish
law. It also voiced its appreciation of the Dutch government's
"willingness to cooperate in the implementation" of the plan.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also calls on the Libyan government to ensure
the appearance in the Netherlands of the two accused, and to
promptly make available at the court any evidence or witnesses in
Libya requested by the court.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also asked U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan to "assist the Libyan government with the physical
arrangements for the transfer of the accused from Libya directly
to the Netherlands."
</P>
<P>
The resolution said actions would be taken to "immediately
suspend" sanctions following the arrival of the two accused in the
Netherlands for the trial. The sanctions, imposed in 1992 to
force Libya to surrender the suspects, ban air travel to and from
the country, freeze some assets abroad and limit sales of oil
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Upon their arrival in the Netherlands, the two alleged bombers
will be detained by the Dutch government pending their transfer
for the purpose of a trial, the resolution added.
</P>
<P>
However, the resolution "expressed its intention to consider
additional measures if the two accused do not arrive or appear for
trial promptly."
</P>
<P>
It also insists that Libya satisfy French authorities
investigating the mid-flight bombing of France's UTA Flight 772
over Niger in 1989 in which 171 people died.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused of blowing up an American airliner
over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988, killing a total of 270
people.
</P>
<P>
China also voted in favor of the resolution. Before the voting
kicked off, Shen Guofang, Chinese acting permanent representative
to the United Nations, said that "part of the draft resolution can
still be improved in order to create a better atmosphere for the
settlement of the problem."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shen reiterated China's reservations over the two
Security Council resolutions, which impose and tighten sanctions
against Libya.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted one day after the Libyan government
announced its acceptance to the change of trial venue, saying "it
will deal positively with this step and will give it the attention
it deserves." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
