<HEADLINE> Thai Police Seize 70,000 Pirated CDs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Thai police have seized more
than 70,000 pirated CD-Roms, video CDs and music CDs with a street
value of more than 20 million baht (500,000 U.S. dollars) in the
biggest haul this year, the Nation newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Two men, suspected to be part of a ring supplying pirated CDs
and CD-Roms to major computer stores, were arrested after a police
raid, the newspaper quoted the Economic Crime Division as saying.
</P>
<P>
Police suspected that the leader of the ring was a Singaporean
man, who is still at large.
</P>
<P>
The haul included 23,433 CDs containing Microsoft software,
2,090 video CDs containing movies from Goldstar Pictures, 1,365
CD-Roms of Sony Entertainment's computer games, and some 52,000
other CD-Roms and pornographic video CDs.
</P>
<P>
Police said most of the CDs were produced in Malaysia and
exported to Singapore before being imported to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Some of the Microsoft software had a registered value of 40,000
dollars, according to the police.
</P>
<P>
Pirated computer CD-Roms sell for between 150 baht to 300 baht
(3.75 dollars to 7.5 dollars) each in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
