<HEADLINE> Thailand Lobbies for hosting Int'l Medical Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Thai public and private
sectors have spent 12 million baht (292,628 U.S. dollars) to lobby
for the right to host an international medical conference in
Bangkok in 2002, according to the Gastro-Enterologists Association
of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Sawat Hitanant, chairman of the association, was quoted Friday
by the Bangkok Post as saying that he was confident that Thailand
would beat Singapore in the selection to be host of the 12th
Organization Mondiale de Gastro-Enterologies (OMGE) meeting, which
is forecast to bring more than 1.5 billion baht (36.5 million U.S.
dollars) into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The association has spent 12 million Baht (292,628 U.S.
dollars), donated by the public and private sectors, to lobby OMGE
countries to vote for the 12th OMGE meeting at the Bangkok
International Trade and Exhibition Center, he said.
</P>
<P>
In March, the association invited representatives of OMGE
members to Thailand and the Foreign Ministry hosted a grant
reception for them, whereas Singapore just organized a cocktail
reception, Sawat said.
</P>
<P>
"If Thailand is selected to host the meeting, Thai doctors and
medical students will have opportunities to learn many things from
physicians worldwide without going abroad," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The country will gain more than 1.5 billion baht (36.5 million
U.S. dollars) from 16,000 meeting participants and their family
members," he said. 
</P>
