<HEADLINE> Ukraine Wants to Settle Accounts With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 27 (Xinhua) -- When it comes to settling debts
between Russia's gas companies and Ukraine's machine industry,
Ukraine is insisting on balancing the accounts, Ukrainian Prime
Minister Valery Pustovoitenko said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told a press conference the method of debt
payment is one of the main issues under discussion with his
Russian counterpart Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
It is a position that Ukraine will adhere to, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko also expressed dissatisfaction with the failure
to carry out a Ukrainian-Russian long-term economic cooperation
treaty, sighed by the two countries' presidents in Moscow last
February. He attributed the failure to Russian inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
On Russian President Boris Yeltsin's naming Chernomyrdin as
acting prime minister, Pustovoitenko said it could be a major
factor in stablizing Russia politically and economically. He hoped
Russia would overcome its current crisis soon.
</P>
<P>
By July this year, Ukraine owed Russia 610 million U.S. dollars
for natural gas supplies. Russia, meanwhile, owned Ukrainian
machinery manufacturers several hundred million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The debt payment is a sticky matter between the two
countries. Last July, the Russian gas giant, Gazprom, temporarily
cut its deliveries to Ukraine by 20 million cubic meters in a bid
to force payment of the burgeoning debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
