<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Early Solution of Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- China on Thursday called
on all parties concerned to strengthen dialogue and consultation
for an early solution of the long-standing Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
But China has reservations on some wording in a just-adopted
U.N. draft resolution, saying that "some elements of the
resolution could have been improved in order to create a better
atmosphere for the settlement of the problem."
</P>
<P>
Under the just-adopted resolution, the Security Council is
expected "to consider additional measures" if Libya failed to
surrender the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
The statement came when Shen Guofang, Chinese acting permanent
representative to the United Nations, took the floor on Thursday
night when the U.N. Security Council was considering a draft
resolution on the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution, introduced by the U.S. and Britain
earlier this week, offered to try the two suspected Libyans of the
Lockerbie bombing in the Netherlands under normal Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
He also asked all concerned to "adopt positive and flexible
attitude towards the Lockerbie issue, reaching an early agreement
on specific aspects of the Lockerbie case by dialogue and
consultation for the early commencement of the trial procedure."
</P>
<P>
China remains firm against terrorism in all its forms and
manifestations, he said, adding that China condemns the Lockerbie
bombing and is deeply concerned over the outstanding issue.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes the new development in the Lockerbie issue, and
hopes such a positive development can be conducive to the early
suspension of sanctions against Libya, which was imposed in 1992,
Shen said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese envoy also voiced his hope that the cooperation
between all concerned parties can be helpful in early
determination of the truth of the Lockerbie case, and bringing
criminals to justice.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that the present development and the
cooperative attitude from the Libyan side will be conducive to a
decision by the Security Council for the lifting of sanctions at
an early date," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also spoke highly of the fruitful efforts by the
Arab League and the Organization of African Unity toward peaceful
solution of the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the Security Council members began to cast their
votes, Shen told reporters that "China's position on the Lockerbie
issue has always been consistent, and we hope the Lockerbie issue
will be solved as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused of blowing up an American airliner
over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988, which killed a total
of 270 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
