<HEADLINE> Security for US Establishments Beefed up in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Police and the military
intelligence force in Thailand have been put on alert against
possible revenge attacks on U.S. business and diplomatic
establishments here after the U.S. missile attacks on targets in
Afghanistan and Sudan last week.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, who is also defense minister,
said after chairing the Defense Council's weekly meeting Thursday
that top military commanders agreed that revenge attacks would
spread and countries with poor security arrangements would be
primary targets.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is worrisome. Terrorist groups will likely
resort to all means to retaliate against the U.S. missile
attacks," the Nation newspaper Friday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
All security units under the police and military control have
been put on alert against possible terrorist activities in
Thailand with extra precautions against "suspicious" foreign
visitors, Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
The move came two days after a pipe bomb exploded in Planet
Hollywood restaurant in Cape Town, South Africa, killing one man
and injuring 27 others. The trendy American restaurant chain also
has a branch in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Police Director General Pracha Promnok has ordered security
beefed up for U.S. businesses and diplomatic establishments as
well as the embassies of Israel, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
