<HEADLINE> Hungarian Economy Stable, Minister Stresses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Hungary's Finance Minister
Jarai Zsigmond said on Thursday that the Russian financial crisis
had brought only slight impact to his country.
</P>
<P>
He told a news conference that Hungary's exports to Russia
accounted for only 4 percent of its total, while 70 percent went
to European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that with a foreign exchange reserves of 9 billion
U.S. dollars, Hungary's economy was stable,
</P>
<P>
However, on the Budapest share market, share prices plunged in
recent days to the level of April 1997, while the Hungarian
currency forint was weakening further.
</P>
<P>
But the minister attributed such a situation to external
factors.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government did not plan to extend the floating
range of forint, nor to raise banks' savings interest rate.
