<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surgical Glue to Replace Stitches Approved By FDA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A super glue-like substance
made by Closure Medical Corp. was approved by U.S. Food and Drug
Administration Thursday for doctors to use in replacement of
stitches on skin-deep wounds.
</P>
<P>
The substance named DermaBond contains a variation of the
chemical used in Super Glue. It could form a flexible film
quickly over the wound that gradually wears off as new skin cells
grow beneath it.
</P>
<P>
According to the company, DermaBond has many advantages: taking
just half as much time to apply as sutures do and, with less
painful without a local anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
DermaBond is designed to replace stitches in skin-deep cuts or
the punctures of minimally invasive surgery. It is for topical
use only not for deep wounds under the skin.
</P>
<P>
However the FDA warned that doctors must thoroughly cleanse the
wound first, so bacteria are not sealed inside, and cannot use
DermaBond on infected wounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
