<BODY>
<HEADLINE> May Riots Provoked by Agitators: Jakarta Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Jakarta Governor Sutiyoso has
acknowledged that the May riots that hit the Indonesian capital
and other cities were provoked by agitators, according to national
newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
After a two-hour hearing here Thursday with the Joint
Fact-Finding Team investigating the riots, Suriyoso said there
were "operators in control of the riots."
</P>
<P>
"They were organized," he was quoted as saying, without
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
Sutiyoso is the second senior official to have testified before
the investigation team. On Wednesday, the team questioned former
Jakarta military commander Maj. Gen. Sjafrie Sjamsoeddin.
</P>
<P>
The investigation team was established by the government last
month to investigate reports that the May riots, in which more
than 1,200 people were killed, were masterminded.
</P>
<P>
Sutiyoso said he revealed everything he knew about the riots to
the investigation team, which is chaired by Bambang Widjojanto.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he deployed civil security officers to safeguard
Jakarta during the riots, he said: "Of course I did. Every officer
in the city was deployed and had been involved in securing the
city."
</P>
<P>
Bambang told reporters the governor was invited by the team to
accommodate them with accurate data about the riots.
</P>
<P>
He said the definition of "agitators", as mentioned by
Sutiyoso, could be groups of individuals acting independently of
one another.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that the groups may have been working in tandem
and following orders to hit certain areas.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian rights activists have said that 168 women and girls,
most of them ethnic Chinese, were raped and sexually assaulted
during the May riots, and about 20 of them died or committed
suicide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
