<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Russia, Belarus Looking for Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Ukraine, Russia and
Belarus have pledged to step up economic cooperation among the
three countries after they met in the Crimean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax-Ukraine reported on Wednesday that the consensus
was reached on Wednesday night when Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma, Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko and Russian
Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin gathered together in
Crimea.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech, Kuchma voiced support for the
Russian-Belarussian Union, which was set up last year.
</P>
<P>
"Russia and Belarus have gained lots of benefits from regional
cooperation," Chernomyrdin said. "But the cooperation between
Russia and Ukraine is a bit different."
</P>
<P>
He said that economic cooperation should be a priority in the
bilateral relations, adding that the two countries could build
more joint ventures and beef up financial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine is always ready to conduct the closest cooperation
with Russia," Kuchma said. He urged Russia to continue the project
of jointly manufacturing the An-70 transport plane.
</P>
<P>
An-70 was jointly designed by Russia and Ukraine and has become
a major rival of the U.S.-made C-130 transport aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, who came to Ukraine for emergent talks with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), also proposed the presidents of
the three countries meet at a border town to discuss trilateral
cooperation. 
</P>
