<HEADLINE> Panama Inaugurates Harpy Eagle Protection Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Panama City dedicated its
first world-level center Thursday for the protection of the
endangered harpy eagle, City Hall spokesman Jose Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
The complex, located in the Summit Botanical Garden in the
outskirts of Panama City, was suggested by an American zoologist,
Ron Magill, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Panama City Mayor's Office, in cooperation with
international corporations, invested more than 1 million
U.S. dollars in the project to protect its national bird, Gonzalez
said.
</P>
<P>
Currently the center is sheltering two birds: a 20-year-old
female and a three-year-old male.
</P>
<P>
"The center also includes an aviary, which provides the birds
with an appropriate environment to live in, while providing people
with an opportunity to observe their development," said Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
An interactive center with modern visual equipment is under
consideration for visitors to the complex to provide all available
information on the harpy eagle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
