<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt to Probe Banking Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
said it would soon send a special team to investigate crimes in
the banking sector, local leading newspapers reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The team will be drawn from the Indonesian Bank Restructuring
Agency (IBRI), the Attorney General Office and the Police, Justice
Minister Muladi was quoted as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The team would investigate all the private banks which had
received liquidity credits from Bank Indonesia, the central bank,
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Under the International Monetary Fund's (IMF) reform package,
banking restructuring is one of Indonesia's top priorities in
efforts to revive the economy.
</P>
<P>
Economists say an unsound banking system greatly contributed to
the country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia is reported to have lent at least 135 trillion
rupiah (12.3 billion U.S. dollars) as of August 14 to the
insolvent banks in the form of liquidity assistance. Some of funds
channeled became bad debts, while others were misused by bankers.
</P>
<P>
"Our priority is to resolve the administrative aspect of the
cases in the civil court so that we can get the money back. Any
criminal charges would follow thereafter," Muladi said.
</P>
<P>
As part of its sweeping economic reforms, the government last
week froze the operation of three private banks, nationalized four
private banks and merged four state banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
