<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs from Latin American Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela has imported 3.873 billion U.S. dollars
worth of non-oil products since the beginning of this year, up
18.2 percent over the same period last year, the Coordination and
Planning Office reported.
</P>
<P>
It said the country's total imports have maintained a steady
growth since November 1996.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional exports rose by only 3.12 percent over the same
period last year, amounting to 2.37 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Shell oil company has invested 200 million
dollars in the purchase of 22.6 percent of the concession to
exploit crude oil and natural gas in Acambuco in Argentina's Salta
province.
</P>
<P>
This is the second Shell acquisition this week in the country's
gas business following a 186-million-dollar purchase announced on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's international cash reserves diminished
by 90 million dollars in the last three months, according to
Central Bank statistics.
</P>
<P>
The drop was caused by a reduction of coffee exports in the
summer months of June, July and August, said Central Bank
President Eduardo Lizano.
</P>
<P>
Coffee exports are Costa Rica's third largest earner of hard
currency, after bananas and tourism.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peru's copper output amounted to 270,000 tons during
the first seven months of this year, down 6.9 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to government estimates, the world's sixth biggest
copper producer is expected to produce a total of 525,500 tons
this year, compared with 502,970 tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Sales of light, medium and heavy trucks in Chile
totaled 5,269 units in the first seven months this year, down 6.8
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Automotive Association of Chile,
trademarks leading the sales list were Chevrolet with 862 units,
Mercedes Benz with 693 units and Ford with 501 units.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama will start negotiations with Central
American countries in September that are expected to lead to the
signing of a free trade agreement, said Panamanian Finance and
Treasury Minister Miguel Heras Castro.
</P>
<P>
The talks will cover services, investments, intellectual
property rights, unfair trade practices, elimination of tariff and
non-tariff barriers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
