<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Quarter Costa Ricans Live Below Subsistence Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Almost one quarter of the Costa
Rican population cannot earn enough to satisfy their basic needs,
said a study published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This means 800,000 people in the country have difficulty in
meeting their lowest demands for food, housing, transportation,
education and other basic services.
</P>
<P>
The subsistence level for a family of four, according to the
Ministry of Economy, is 127,000 colons (490 U.S. dollars) per
month. However, most workers can only earn the minimum salary of
75,000 colons (290 dollars).
</P>
<P>
As a result, a large number of women have to go out to find a
job. At present, women make up 30 percent of the labor force,
said Henry Mora, director of the School of Economy of the National
University.
</P>
<P>
Because of families' difficulty in making ends meet, children
are also found seeking jobs in the labor market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
