<HEADLINE> Thailand's Motor Vehicle Production Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's production of motor
vehicles, excluding motorcycles, fell 73 percent in the first
seven months of this year as compared with the same period last
year, according to figures compiled by the Federation of Thai
Industry available Friday.
</P>
<P>
Vehicle production from January to July this year totalled
78,105 unit, down by 211,142 units from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
During the period, 16,918 passenger cars were produced
representing 21.66 percent of total vehicle production, but down
73,953 units or 81.38 percent from the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
Truck production was down from 136,448 to 59,926.
</P>
<P>
Motorcycle production totalled 375,270 units, down 365,738 or
49.36 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Vehicle exports reached 30,659 units, up 11,642 units
or 61.22 percent. Export value jumped by 178.3 million U.S.
dollars or 117.42 percent, to 332.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports of car engines declined by 11.6 million U.S. dollar, or
43.84 percent, to 14.9 million U.S. dollars, while those of other
car parts rose by 22.5 million U.S. dollars, or 73.1 percent to
53.4 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Motorcycle exports rose by 44,295 units or 59.21 percent, to
119,102 units. Their export value jumped by 46.4 million U.S.
dollars or 76.89 percent, to 106.8 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
