<HEADLINE> U.S. Scolds Germany, Austria Over Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States criticized
Germany and Austria on Thursday for pushing Bosnian refugees to
return home.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is expected to raise the
issue in Vienna next week.
</P>
<P>
"One of our real concerns right now is that Germany (and)
Austria are pushing too hard to encourage the return of Bosnian
refugees for ... understandable domestic reasons," said a senior
U.S. official at a briefing on Albright's trip to Europe next week.
</P>
<P>
Starting Saturday, Albright will visit Croatia and Bosnia, then
go to Moscow for a U.S.-Russian summit before spending a few hours
in the Austrian capital on September 3.
</P>
<P>
The official said the main purpose of her trip to Vienna is to
acknowledge Austria's role as current president of the European
Union, but added that the issue on refugees will be on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The official said that unless there is careful planning,
refugees tend to go to areas where their ethnic group is in the
majority rather than to their original homes, where other ethnic
groups might now be in control.
</P>
<P>
The United States had proposed to the European Union to work on
a program to make sure that returns took place "in a carefully
managed environment," he added.
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 refugees have returned to Bosnia in the last six
weeks, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He said the German government was "extremely unhappy" about
past U.S. criticism of its refugee policy.
</P>
<P>
The official charged that European governments had failed to
respond adequately to an appeal for funds to train and equip local
police in Bosnia. Germany had provided no funds for this purpose,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of Albright's trip to Bosnia is to demonstrate
U.S. support for the elections next month. "In many ways, this
will be the first real post-war elections," said the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
