<HEADLINE> Nestle Tries to Increase Market Share in Central Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Nestle-Sofia's main objective is
to become the main chocolate and confectionary producer among
Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) member states, the
company's Director General Mitris Koronakis said at a news
conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nestle-Sofia, a subsidiary of the Swiss Nestle company, is
marketing 7 to 12 percent of its output in the former Soviet
Republics, Hungary and South Africa. The percentage is expected to
increase to 20 percent soon.
</P>
<P>
Nestle-Sofia is to introduce some 26 new products here,
Koronakis said, adding that the company will also import three
kinds of Delly Super chocolate desserts by mid-September along
with 11 kinds of sugar and caramel sweets.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to sell the products at the same prices across the
country despite transportation costs," Nestle Sales Director
George Makridimitris said.
</P>
<P>
The new distribution network of the company, employing 150
distributors and 120 light and heavy duty trucks, went into
operation this week. 
</P>
