<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, August 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
Thursday as the global financial markets were affected by Russian
and Asian economic crises.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 142.18 yen,
down from 144.02 late Wednesday. It also was trading at 1.7941
marks, down from 1.8061 marks, and 1.5788 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.5677. (NY-Dollar Falling)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Northern Irish police said Thursday it was a step
closer to catching the Omagh bombers after the police
reconstructed the bomb timer used in the
blast. (UK-N.Ireland-Omagh)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Researchers at a Dallas-based company said
Wednesday that they have developed leading-edge semiconductor
technology based on the smallest announced transistors in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Featuring an effective channel length of 0.07 micron -- 1,000
times thinner than a human hair -- the transistors are so
miniscule that more than 400 million of them will fit onto a
single chip the size of a fingernail, said Texas Instrument in the
announcement. (US-Chips)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno announced
Thursday that two suspects in the U.S. embassy bombing in Nairobi,
Kenya, had been brought to the United States for trial.
</P>
<P>
The two suspects are Khalid Salim, whose real name is Mohammed
Rashid Daoud al-O'whali, and Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, both of whom
are said to be linked to Islamic militant financier Osama bin
Laden. (US-Embassy Bombings-Trial)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African police Thursday detained a man
and two women for questioning in connection with the terrible
bombing in a Cape Town restaurant Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three were arrested Thursday afternoon at the Cape Town
international airport where they have boarded an aircraft bound
for Cairo, Egypt, South African television
reported. (SAfrica-Blast Suspects)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
