<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sets Up Grand Theater </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shanghai has built
a grand theater where the China National Ballet Troupe will
perform "Swan Lake."
</P>
<P>
The new 11,500-sq.m. Shanghai Opera House has become another
landmark for the metropolis, northwest of the People's Square in
the center of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the 1.2-billion-yuan (about 150 million
U.S. dollars) building started four years ago. It was designed by
a French architect, with a mixture of futuristic design and
romantic oriental art.
</P>
<P>
The 10-storey building has a 1,800-seat theater for opera,
ballet, and orchestras, a 600-seat concert hall, and a 200-seat
hall for drama and dance.
</P>
<P>
The major theater has the largest computerized stage-control
system in Asia. The stage consists of a 728-sq.m. front section, a
360-sq.m. back section, and two 257-sq.m. side sections.
</P>
<P>
The sections can be raised and can turn in all directions. The
eight backdrops can be changed automatically. The theater is also
equipped with state-of-the-art acoustics, dressing rooms,
rehearsal halls, and service centers.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Teatro Comunale Di Firenze, St. Petersburg's Maninsky
Theater, and the NHK Symphony Orchestra of Japan will perform in
the theater in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
