<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christie Sets for Comeback Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Former Olympic champion Linford
Christie of Britain is poised to come out of retirement for a
one-off appearance in the grand prix meeting in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The former Olympic 100m champion has been invited to run the
anchor leg in a sprint relay alongside some of Britain's European
Championship heroes.
</P>
<P>
"It is very possible Linford will be running," Christie's
manager Sue Barrett confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Linford has been asked to run and he is considering it,
though no final decision has been made."
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old, whose last race was more than a year ago, is
scheduled to join new European 100m champion Darren Campbell and
Dwain Chambers in the relay team.
</P>
<P>
Both runners been inspired by Christie's achievements in
international athletics.
</P>
<P>
Campbell is coached by Christie and Chambers is managed by his
company, 'Nuff Respect.
</P>
<P>
The relay quartet will be completed by either double world
junior champion Christian Malcolm or European 200m bronze
medalist Julian Golding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
