<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Falls Along with Stock Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against
most major currencies Thursday as the global financial markets
were affected by Russian and Asian economic crises.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican peso dropped to another record low, as did the
Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 142.18 yen,
down from 144.02 late Wednesday. It also was trading at 1.7941
marks, down from 1.8061 marks, and 1.5788 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.5677.
</P>
<P>
The Russian central bank suspended dollar trading to preserve
its dwindling foreign reserves for the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
A number of countries intervened in foreign exchange markets or
raised interest rates. But none of those actions could protect
their currencies from falling.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4809 Swiss francs, down from 1.5059; 6.0135 French
francs, down from 6.0545; 1,775.00 Italian lire, down from
1,781.50.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6523 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6385 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
