<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Dollar Drops Despite Rates Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The battered Canadian dollar
continued its free fall Thursday despite of a one-percentage-point
interest rates hike by the Bank of Canada.
</P>
<P>
To prop up Canada's currency, the loonie, the central bank
raised its bank rates to 6.0 percent Thursday, a stern medicine it
had previously refused to deliver for fearing of slowing down the
economy.
</P>
<P>
The loonie rebounded briefly, then plunged to an all-time low
of 63.09 cents U.S. during the day. It closed at 63.31 cents U.S.,
down 0.57 of a cent.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's rates hike came after the Canadian dollar made a new
record low Wednesday, dropping for the first time below 64 cents
U.S. in its 140-year history.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Canada said the increase in interest rates "is
aimed at providing support for the Canadian dollar in order to
bolster confidence."
</P>
<P>
Yet, so far the move has been proved to be futile. The bank
does not have enough power to stop the falling of the dollar in
the current turmoils of Asia and Russian financial crises, some
economists say.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of this year, the Canadian dollar has lost more
than 11 percent of its value against the strong U.S. dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
