<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect Charged with Murder for Nairobi Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A suspect in the bombing of the
U.S. embassy in Nairobi was charged with murder by Manhattan
federal prosecutors on Thursday, 20 days after the incident which
killed 257 and wounded more than 5000.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Rashed Daoud Al-'Owhali, also known as Khalid Salim
Saleh Bin Rashed, was ordered detained pending a September 28
appearance.
</P>
<P>
The 14-count complaint by the Federal Bureau of Investigation
(FBI) charged the defendant with murder, murder conspiracy and use
of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The complaint charged that he confessed to his role in the
bombing and said he would die as a "martyr" on August 7, the day
of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The complaint said the plot began in March and the defendant
admitted that on August 7, he threw a "small grenade-like device"
toward a guard outside the U.S. embassy in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
According to court papers, Owhali was arrested by Kenyan
officials two days after the bombing and turned over to the FBI
later.
</P>
<P>
He confessed that he was trained in explosives, hijacking and
kidnapping in camps in Afghanistan, including attending meetings
and conferences chaired by terrorist financier Bin Laden chased by
the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Owhali was flown by the FBI to New York on Wednesday night, FBI
Director Louis J. Freeh told a press conference in Washington
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno who joined the press conference
together with other senior Administration officials, described
Owhali's arrest as "the most extensive overseas investigation" in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
Another suspect of the bombing, Mohammed Sadiq Odeh, was sent
to the U.S. on Thursday for trial.
</P>
<P>
Odeh had been held by Kenyan authorities since August 14 after
his arrest in Karachi, pakistan, on the day of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said several other suspects held in Kenya could
also be sent to the U.S. for trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
