<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Introduces School Safety Guide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday introduced a new education guide to help prevent school
violence and ordered the expansion of the Police Corps.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Worcester, Massachusetts, Clinton said the "Early
Warning, Timely Response: A Guide to Safe Schools" was to help
educators, parents and fellow students to recognize and then
respond to early-warning signs.
</P>
<P>
It will help schools to recognize a troubled or potentially
violent young person, and it outlines steps to intervene early,
before it is too late, Clinton explained.
</P>
<P>
The guide, which was developed by the Department of Education
and the Department of Justice following a series of school
shootings earlier this year, will be distributed to every school
before the start of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also ordered the expansion of the Police Corps to
provide more college scholarships, with preference given to the
children of police officers killed in duty.
</P>
<P>
"The fight against crime is, in the last analysis, a fight to
preserve that quality of community which is at the root of our
greatness, a fight to preserve confidence in ourselves and in our
fellow citizens, a battle for the quality of our lives," Clinton
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
