<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges in Global Selloff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Dow industrials plunged 357
points Thursday, its third-biggest point loss ever and the biggest
percentage drop since last October's tumbling.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street's plummet in heavy trading happened as Russia's
worsening economic crisis and disappointment for Japan's efforts
to revive its crippling economy sent stocks down around the globe.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 357.36, or by 4.2
percent, to 8,165.99, according to closing figures.
</P>
<P>
The drop left the Dow 1,171 points, or 12.6 percent, below its
July 17 record high closing of 9,337.97. A drop of 10 percent is
considered a "correction," while a sustained decline of 20 percent
marks a bear market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, which once was up 18.1 percent this year, is now up
just 3.3 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The slide of 357 points was the third-biggest point drop ever,
behind the record 554.26 points of October 27, 1997, and the
508-point "Black Monday" crash of October 19, 1987. In percentage
terms, the 4.2 percent tumble was the biggest since the 7.2
percent drop of last October's plunge but far behind Black
Monday's 22.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 slid 40.03 to 1,044.15, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index skidded 77.27 to 1,690.86.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 15-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled a scorching
934.66 million shares, as against 671.85 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index dropped 20.74 to 518.82, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 24.84 to 169.08
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 14.33 to
366.09.
</P>
<P>
Prices soared on long-term U.S. Treasury bonds, while bond
yields, which move in the opposite direction of prices, fell to
5.35 percent. It would be the lowest closing level ever since the
government began regular sales of the 30-year bonds in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Tokyo's main stock index fell by more than 3
percent to its lowest close in more than six years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Commerce Department Thursday reported economic
growth cooled off to a seasonally adjusted 1.6 percent annual rate
in the second quarter of this year from 5.5 percent in the first
three months of 1998. Corporate profits edged up just 0.3 percent
in the second quarter and were down 1.5 percent from a year ago,
the first year-to-year drop since 1989.
</P>
<P>
Europe's main markets also sank, with their main indexes
going down by big margins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
