<HEADLINE> Cuban Exiles Plead Innocent to Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Four Cuban exiles pleaded
innocent Thursday in Puerto Rico to charges that they plotted to
kill Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
The four were among seven exiles, including a director of the
Cuban American National Foundation, the most influential Cuban
exile group, indicted by a federal grand jury in San Juan Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The case is believed to be the first such court case after
years of alleged plots against Castro. They were freed on bail by
the U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
It could be months before the case comes to trial. The FBI said
more arrests and indictments were expected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Attorney General Janet Reno was asked Thursday
whether the indictment represented a change in U.S. policy, and
she said she was not aware of any change.
</P>
<P>
The indictment was believed as a blow to the Miami-based Cuban
American National Foundation, of which he is a director. Castro
has accused the foundation of plotting to kill him, but the group
says it is committed to peaceful political persuasion.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the State Department denied the idea that the
indictment implied that the administration is changing its
policies towards Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
