<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Two Credits for Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved here
Thursday two interest-free credits totaling 126 million U.S.
dollars for an urban transport improvement and a higher education
projects in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
First credit of 42.7 million dollars equivalent is provided for
the urban transport improvement project. This project's overall
objective is to increase operational efficiency and safety on
selected corridors and in the central areas of Hanoi and HCMC.
</P>
<P>
To improve traffic, it will introduce a package of traffic
engineering and management measures that will redesign junctions,
provide new traffic signals and controls, segregate
two-and-four-wheeled traffic, and improve facilities for
pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
Another credit of 83.3 million dollars equivalent will be used
for the higher education project in the country.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to increase coherence, flexibility, and
responsiveness of higher education to the changing demands of
society and the market economy.
</P>
<P>
The project is also designed to improve the quality of
curriculum, teaching, learning and research in higher education.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessional
lending wing for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
