<HEADLINE> N.Irish Police: Step Closer to Finding Omagh Bombers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Northern Irish police said
Thursday it was a step closer to catching the Omagh bombers after
the police reconstructed the bomb timer used in the blast.
</P>
<P>
"We have been virtually able to reconstruct the timing-power
unit of this bomb," said Ronnie Flanagan, head of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary police in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
"We know that unit is very similar to units that have been used
in perhaps the last five or six explosive attacks carried out by
the so-called Real IRA," BBC quoted him as saying at a news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
The Real IRA, a splinter republican group, admitted planting
the bomb in a shopping center in Omagh which killed 28 people and
injured 220 others nearly two weeks ago. The group declared a
cease-fire four days after the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Flanagan said the device had been contained in a small plastic
sandwich box, and urged shopowners to contact the RUC or the Irish
police if they had recently sold these items.
</P>
<P>
He also said other leads were being followed and he was
confident of finding those responsible for the Omagh atrocity.
</P>
</TEXT>
