<HEADLINE> Security Council to Vote on Draft Lockerbie Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Security Council
members are expected to cast their votes late Thursday on a draft
resolution, offered by America and Britain to endorse a plan to
try the two suspected Libyans in the Lockerbie case.
</P>
<P>
Danilo Turk, president of the 15-member Security Council told
reporters here that "the council has decided to convene this
evening for a formal meeting to take action on the resolution."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council went on with informal consultations on
Thursday morning to ponder over the draft resolution, which
proposed an endorsement to an American-British plan to hold the
trial of the two accused Libyans in the Netherlands under the
normal Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
However, the draft resolution proposed "additional measures"
against Libya "if the two accused have not arrived or appeared
for trial promptly," diplomatic sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused of blowing up an American
Airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988, which
claimed 270 lives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
