<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Economies Seen to Grow 1.8 Percent This Year and Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in the G-7
industrialized nations will average 1.8 percent for both this year
and next, an economic think-tank predicted here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices of these seven countries will rise by only 1.4
percent in 1998 and 1.8 percent in 1999, according to the 1998
Summer World Outlook by the Conference Board of Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Japan remains the principal brake on G-7 growth," said Peter
Lok, author of the economic report.
</P>
<P>
"With personal consumption and business investment continuing
to tumble, the outlook for Japan remains bleak. And Japan, being
the dominant economy in Asia, is dragging the region into
recession," he said.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted a slow and painful recovery will begin in
Japan in 1999, with economic activity expanding by only 1.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the North American economy remains robust.
Economic growth will reach 3.1 percent this year before slowing
down to two percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices in the region are forecast to rise by an
average of only 1.8 percent this year but will accelerate to 2.9
percent in 1999 as growth begins to pick up again in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The economies of Western Europe, as a whole, will post a
moderate growth of 2.8 percent this year and 2.7 percent in 1999
with the major economies moving in various directions, according
to the forecast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
