<HEADLINE> Vietnam, St. Petersburg Increase Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese President Tran Duc
Luong, who on Thursday left Moscow for St. Petersburg to continue
his visit to Russia, and Governor of St. Petersburg Vladimir
Yakovlev have reached an agreement on all-round cooperation,
according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese president said that during his meeting with the
governor of St. Petersburg they exchanged views and agreed on
issues of all-round cooperation between St. Pertersburg and the
Republic of Vietnam, as well as Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
St. Petersburg used to have close economic, scientific and
cultural ties with Vietnam and was a sister-city with Ho Chi Minh
city.
</P>
<P>
Governor Yakovlev said that the city administration was
interested in Vietnamese business people coming to St. Pertersburg
and Vietnam's state orders being placed at city enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to Yakovlev, the two sides also agreed on other
issues, including the revival of the twin-cities ties between
St.Petersburg and Ho Chi Minh city, the mutual trade and the
establishment of a network of Vietnamese restaurants in St.
Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese president arrived in Moscow on Monday on an
official visit to Russia. He has met with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin in Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
