<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papantoniou: Greek Drachma Not Affected Directly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Greek National Economy and
Finance Minister Yiannos Papantoniou said Thursday that the Greek
national currency, drachma, was not affected directly by Russia's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that it suffered certain pressures due to the
liquidation of earnings from the Greek treasury bills as it had
happened with the treasury bills of other European governments.
</P>
<P>
Describing the crisis in Russia as "the result of the problems
in the political and structural policy, he said that all the
European economies with significant economic, trade and banking
transactions with Russia and Asian money markets have been
affected by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Bank of Greece and the Greek
government closely follow the developments and would take all
necessary measures for the normalization of the situation.
</P>
<P>
Worries over the crisis in Russia put intense pressure on the
Greek economy and the drachma Wednesday hit fresh lows against the
mark and other major currencies, amid a sell-off in government
bonds.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the total outflow came to 1.7 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
To defend the bond market and the drachma, the Greek central
bank intervened heavily in the domestic markets by spending 1.2
billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
