<HEADLINE> China: Scott Ritter's Resignation Not to Affect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The resignation by an
American U.N. weapons inspector would not affect U.N. weapons
inspection in Iraq, China said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Scott Ritter on Wednesday quitted his post in the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, and his resignation was
accepted immediately by UNSCOM Executive Chairman Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
In his letter of resignation, Ritter strongly criticized the
U.N. Secretary-General and the Security Council for being too weak
to take tougher stance towards the recent standoff between Iraq
and UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions by reporters on the resignation,
Chinese Deputy Permanent Representative to the United Nations Shen
Guofang said he was not surprised at Ritter's resignation, and
Ritter's departure can not and would not affect UNSCOM's work in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Shen said Ritter's comments on the Security Council were his
personal opinions, and the Security Council has always urged the
comprehensive implementation of its relevant resolutions by
calling for Iraq 's fully compliance as well as acknowledging the
progress made in the areas of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
