<HEADLINE> Mozambique Condemns Blast in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Foreign Affairs
and Cooperation Ministry issued a statement Thursday, condemning
the blast in South Africa's Cape Town, which killed at least two
and injured 25 others.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "at a time when the international
community is trying to eliminate international terrorism, we
strongly condemn this act of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Terrorism constitutes a serious threat to world peace and
security, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred Tuesday at a U.S. franchised Planet
Hollywood Restaurant in central Cape Town. It appeared to be
linked to U.S. strikes against alleged Moslem terrorists in Sudan
and Afghanistan last week.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has expressed its shock at the
incident and pledged to bring the bombers to law.
</P>
<P>
Security has been stepped up in South Africa in general and in
Durban in particular to secure delegates of 113 countries at the
forthcoming Non-Aligned Movement summit which opens Saturday
after the bombing in Cape Town. 
</P>
