<HEADLINE> Arab League: Libya Needs Time to Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Assistant Secretary
General Ahmad Adel Thursday underlined the necessity of giving
Libya enough time to study the U.S.-British proposal on settling
the Libya-West Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
Adel, speaking to Egypt's Middle East News Agency, said that he
underlined the importance of giving Libya time to consider
measures and get clarifications on this score during his meeting
Thursday with the political affairs department chief of
U.S. Embassy in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Adel said AL officials have held two rounds of talks with the
U.S. official since Wednesday on the U.S.-British initiative which
was announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Libya late Wednesday accepted the U.S.-British proposal that
the two Libyan suspects in the 1988 bombing of an American plane
be tried by a panel of three Scottish judges under Scottish law in
the Hague, The Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in an interview with the U.S. Cable News Network,
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi said he does not trust the United
States and Britain, saying they may play tricks in handing the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi also said time is needed to study the proposal and "more
details must be worked out, adding the suspects are human beings,
not "tins of fruits."
</P>
<P>
He also demanded the U.N. sanctions imposed on Libya since 1992
to force the handing over of the suspects to be lifted. They ban
air travel and arms sale and include financial restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have long urged Libya to hand over the two
suspects to stand trial in either of the two countries. But
Libya's refusal to comply incurred the U.N. air and arms embargo
in 1992. The bombing killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is discussing a proposal by the
U.S. and Britain on suspending the U.N. sanctions against Libya if
the two suspects are received in The Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
