<HEADLINE> Yeltsin's Resignation Refuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Russian presidential press
service Thursday night officially refuted allegations of impending
resignation of President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
In the fax release the press service said that any information
about allegedly forthcoming resignation of the Russian President
is invented and false.
</P>
<P>
It said that Yeltsin executes the whole fullness of power in
accordance with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The presidential press service, meanwhile, asked CBS and other
foreign mass media not to spread inaccurate information and not to
impede the preparation of the official visit to Russia of U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Presidential press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky Thursday also
refuted the rumor that Yeltsin may resign, saying it is absolutely
untrue.
</P>
<P>
"No resignation has been on the agenda. Let's calm down and
take up real problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
The economic and monetary crisis in Russia is deteriorating
rapidly since Yeltsin dismissed Sergei Kiriyenko's government
entirely on August 23.  
</P>
