<HEADLINE> U.S. Prepares for Summit Despite Turmoil in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The White House said on
Thursday that U.S.-Russia summit preparations still continued
Thursday despite the political and economic crisis in Russia.
</P>
<P>
"This is an extraordinarily important relationship," said Sandy
Berger, the U.S. national security adviser, referring to the
U.S.-Russia summit, which is scheduled to be convened next week in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Berger cautioned that if the newly revamped Russian government
veered away from economic and political reform, "if it changed
fundamentally, that would be of serious concern to us."
</P>
<P>
"It's appropriate the trip continue, and I wouldn't speculate
on any other scenario," Berger told reporters at a news conference
at the Justice Department on the prospective trial of suspects in
the August 7 bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
In response to questions on a report Yeltsin had signed an
undated resignation document, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright told reporters: "we have had no confirmation or comment
on that."
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Massachusetts island of Martha's Vineyard,
where President Bill Clinton is vacationing, said that Clinton
also refused to answer questions from reporters about the
resignation reports.
</P>
<P>
Dimitri K. Simes, president of the Nixon Center, a
Washington-based research center, said Yeltsin has lost all
credibility with the Russian people, and a majority think he
should resign.
</P>
<P>
"The Yeltsin period is coming to an end. The sooner the
better," said the longtime Russia analyst.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton should postpone his visit to Russia. "I have no
idea why President Clinton is going to Moscow," Simes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
