<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges Dispelling of Frustration Over Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa urged all parties in the Middle East peace process to
dispel the sense of frustration.
</P>
<P>
"There is no guarantee of peaceful coexistence but an action on
the ground for establishing peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the call while commenting on a bomb explosion in
Tel Aviv Thursday morning, in which 21 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Palestinian-Israeli direct peace talks, on and
off, since July 19 on Israeli troops redeployment in the West
Bank, Moussa said he did not rule out the possibility of clinching
a deal by September 13 as announced by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
September 13 marks the fifth anniversary of the singing of the
Oslo Accord, which kicks off the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are haggling over the scope of redeployment and
no signs of development toward an agreement have been reported.
</P>
<P>
"It is hoped for, especially if the parties reached balanced
and just commitments based on the U.S. initiative. However, there
are no reports yet available on any progress regarding the set
terms."
</P>
<P>
"It is, anyway, up to the Palestinians to decide. The agreement
has to do with their future commitments and the way the
Palestinian peace track would move," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt prefers a balanced and unconditioned agreement be
reached so that the Palestinian side could accept it easily," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
