<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Interests Make Donations to Congressional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, who isn't up for re-election until 2000, raised almost
100,000 dollars in three months from health-related groups while
senators considered whether to impose new rules on health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
Much of that money will go to help his party's incumbents and
challengers.
</P>
<P>
Lott and other top Republican leaders in both the House of
Representatives and Senate run their own leadership political action
committees (PACs). Between January 1, 1997, and June 30, 1988,
Lott's New Republican Majority Fund gave 306,480 dollars to other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
"It's self-evident in the name of the PAC," said Lott spokesman
John Czwartacki. "Money in politics is not insignificant. It's an
important component to keeping and maintaining the Republican
majority."
</P>
<P>
Critics say these leadership PACs serve as another conduit for
special interest groups to aid lawmakers who control the
congressional agenda. Special interest committees are limited to
giving 10,000 dollars to a lawmaker's campaign, but they can give
another 10,000 dollars to the same lawmaker's leadership
committee.
</P>
<P>
"It's a very convenient way to double your contributions," said
Larry Makinson, director of the nonpartisan Center for Responsive
Politics, which tracks campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
From the start of 1997 through June 30 of this year, the top
four House Republican leaders -- Speaker Newt Gingrich, Majority
Leader Dick Armey, Majority Whip Tom DeLay and Conference Chairman
John Boehner -- reported raising 3.4 million dollars for their
leadership PACs, according to reports to the Federal Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
During the same year and a half, the top four Senate Republican
leaders -- Lott, Assistant Majority Leader Don Nickles, Conference
Chairman Connie Mack and Conference Secretary Paul Coverdell --
took in 5.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Only two Democratic congressional leaders, both in the House,
have PACs. Minority Leader Dick Gephardt took in 686,485 dollars
over 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The top four House Republican leaders gave a total of 1.1
million dollars from their PACs to congressional candidates
between January 1, 1997, and June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers said they did not target specific industries as
donors to their PACs. At a time when Congress tackled proposals to
regulate managed care, the health care industry was a big giver.
</P>
<P>
Players in another major issue before Congress this year --
anti-smoking legislation -- also contributed thousands of dollars
to leadership PACs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weakening Hurricane May Bring Flooding in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Bonnie was
downgraded to a tropical storm on Thursday as it dragged itself
slowly across eastern North Carolina, but pouring rain threatens
flooding in some eastern areas of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Since landing on the East Coast with 185 kph wind Wednesday
afternoon, Bonnie had quickly slowed to a crawl and gradually lost
strength. On Thursday morning, its sustained wind was down to 104
kph, below the minimum hurricane strength of 119 kph.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of widespread damage, injuries or deaths,
but nearly 400,000 customers lost power in the South and North
Carolina, where about half a million people had evacuated before
the storm came.
</P>
<P>
Between Cape Fear and Wilmington, Bonnie's wind peeled the roof
off one wing of a hospital, forcing the evacuation of several
patients. A 40-foot section of windows was blown out of a
Wilmington high school.
</P>
<P>
Streets were filled with tree limbs and debris Thursday at
Morehead City, located on Bogue Sound on North Carolina's central
coast, after a night of being blasted by wind and rain.
</P>
<P>
Some tornadoes in Beaufort and Tyrell counties in North Carolina
caused scattered damage.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain fell Thursday morning in New Bern and Morehead City,
but the rain had trailed off to a drizzle at Wilmington, near the
spot where Bonnie roared ashore.
</P>
<P>
Severe flooding was threatened as the Neuse River was already
out of its banks Thursday morning at New Bern, near the central
North Carolina coast. Many streets were impassable and 770 people
were in shelters.
</P>
<P>
The Pamlico River was over its banks at Washington in Beaufort
County, more than 160 kilometers northeast of Wilmington, and
water closed major highways near New Bern and eastward to Morehead
City on Bogue Sound.
</P>
<P>
Bonnie's eye came ashore at Cape Fear at 2 p.m. Wednesday. By 1
p.m. Thursday it was centered about 110 kilometers south-southwest
of Elizabeth City and moving slowly northeastward at 10 kph,
roughly paralleling the coast but some 110 kilometers inland.
</P>
<P>
It was expected to continue moving toward the northeast. The
heart of the storm was expected to cross Virginia's Norfolk area
later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, Hurricane Danielle was over the Atlantic, about 480
kilometers northeast of the northern Leeward Islands. It was
moving toward the west-northwest at 29 kph with wind of about 145
kph and was expected to strengthen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
