<HEADLINE> GCC Keen to Enhance Ties With Iran, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) is keen to enhance ties with Iran on bases that would secure
stability in the Gulf region, it was learnt at a GCC foreign
ministerial meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah, also Kuwaiti first
deputy prime minister, made the remark when chairing the opening
session of the 68th foreign ministers' meeting of the GCC, which
opened late Thursday in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, to discuss a number
of regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Iranian government to give response to the
calls to resolve the dispute over the Greater and Lesser Tonbs,
and Abu Musa Island with the United Arab Emirates (UAE) peacefully
in accordance with the international laws, Kuwait's official news
agency Kuna reported.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and GCC countries used to be cool due to
political, religious and border disputes. A thaw has been seen
since the Iranian moderate president Mohammad Hatami took power a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sabah said the Gulf Arab bloc is following with
concern the development of the latest crisis between the United
Nations and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's suspension of cooperation with U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) on disarmament of Iraq violated the deal it signed with
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan last February, and the Security
Council resolutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, Sabah voiced GCC's great
concern over the peace process which has been deadlocked since
March 1997.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve a lasting peace in the region, Israel
should withdraw from all occupied Arab territories, including
Jerusalem, the Golan Heights, south Lebanon and western Bekaa of
Lebanon in accordance with the Security Council resolutions and
land-for-peace formula, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports by Kuna said that during the two-day meeting,
GCC foreign ministers would also review the growing issue of
terrorism, and would reiterate the initial stance of their
countries underlining the importance of international cooperation
to combat terrorism within the framework of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo crisis and the situations in Afghanistan, Somalia
and Kashmir would also be discussed.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the ministerial meeting, GCC economic and
finance ministers would assess the latest Gulf efforts aimed at
establishing a custom union among the six member states, namely,
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, they will brief the foreign ministers at a joint
session the outcome of their discussion on the tariffs
integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
