<HEADLINE> U.S. Reiterates Commitment to Cyprus Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. assured Cyprus Thursday
that the settlement of the Cyprus problem still remains a priority
in U.S. diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
The message was contained in a letter by James Steinberg,
President Bill Clinton's deputy assistant, to the ongoing
conference of Cypriot expatriates in Nicosia, a press release
issued at the conference said.
</P>
<P>
Steinberg said that "I can assure you that the Cyprus problem
remains a priority for President Clinton. He is very focused on
it, is very knowledgeable and puts in an enormous amount of time."
</P>
<P>
Clinton "is personally engaged in a search for a solution and
that's why he has engaged top diplomats such as Presidential
Emissary Richard Holbrooke and U.S. ambassador to Cyprus, Kenneth
Brill," Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is a major broker in the Cyprus peace talks, which
have been deadlocked since last summer when Turkish Cypriots opted
out of the U.N.-sponsored negotiations to protest against a
European Union decision to start accession talks with Cyprus, but
not their close ally Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke and Brill have visited Cyprus in the past few months,
but they failed to bring the two sides to back to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
Steinberg stressed that "a commitment is needed by all of us to
achieve and negotiate a solution ... we will make every effort and
urge you to use your own efforts toward this end."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
