<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Suspects Detained For Cape Town Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- South African police
Thursday detained a man and two women for questioning in
connection with the terrible bombing in a Cape Town restaurant
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three were arrested Thursday afternoon at the Cape Town
international airport where they have boarded an aircraft bound
for Cairo, Egypt, South African television reported.
</P>
<P>
Police said the arrest followed an anonymous tip-off.
</P>
<P>
A person was killed and 27 others injured when a bomb exploded
at the U.S.-franchised Planet Hollywood restaurant at the Cape
Town waterfront Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
It appears to be linked to U.S. strikes against alleged Moslem
terrorists in Sudan and Afghanistan last week.
</P>
<P>
A local vigilante group, People Against Gangsterism and Drugs
(Pagad), has confirmed that one of the suspects is its member.
</P>
<P>
Pagad, which is reported to be linked to Moslem
fundamentalists, was involved in continuous skirmishes with local
druglords. There were numerous bombings in recent months in Cape
Town due to their ongoing conflict.
</P>
<P>
Two of the three people, a man and a woman, were questioned by
a senior police officer who is also the investigating officer in
the bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
However, police denied that the detention of the three people
was linked with the bombing. They said there were discrepancies
in the three's travel documents and that they were being held
under the Aliens Control Act.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, President Nelson Mandela visited the bomb
scene. He repeated his condemnation of the bomber's "fully
cowardly deed".
</P>
<P>
A team of bomb disposal experts from the U.S. Federal Bureau
of Investigation (FBI) joined the South African police Thursday
morning in sifting through the debris at the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
The FBI agents came from Nairobi, where they have been probing
the recent twin blasts in U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi said the FBI
investigators will work closely with local police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
