<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Trial of Bombing Suspects for Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno announced Thursday that two suspects in the U.S. embassy
bombing in Nairobi, Kenya, had been brought to the United States
for trial.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Reno said the United States had
mounted the most extensive overseas criminal investigation in its
history in the wake of the bomb attack that killed 258 people,
including 12 Americans, and injured well over 5,000.
</P>
<P>
"Today we have results. A great wrong has been done.... We are
not going to rest. We are not going to forget. We are going to
pursue every last murderer until justice is done," Reno told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The two suspects are Khalid Salim, whose real name is Mohammed
Rashid Daoud al-O'whali, and Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, both of whom
are said to be linked to Islamic militant financier Osama bin
Laden.
</P>
<P>
Salim arrived in New York Wednesday night, FBI Director Louis
Freeh said at the news conference. Odeh's arrival was not
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
Freeh said Salim was trained in a number of camps in
Afghanistan, affiliated with a militant group, Al Kheda, which was
led by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
Mary Jo White, U.S. attorney, Southern District of New York,
told the news conference that a 14-count federal criminal
complaint was unsealed in New York, charging Salim for his
participation in the bombing of the U.S. embassy in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
"The defendant is charged with murder... conspiracy to commit
murder, and conspiracy to use a weapon of mass destruction against
the U.S. embassy in Kenya," White said.
</P>
<P>
Salim was arrested by the Kenyan authorities two days after the
embassy bombing, and then turned over to the FBI. He admitted to
have tossed a grenade at a guard stationed outside the U.S.
embassy at the start of the bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
Salim had been identified as being from Yemen but Yamen's
officials denied it.
</P>
<P>
Odeh was arrested on the day of the bombing in Karachi,
Pakistan, and has been held by Kenyan authorities since Aug. 14.
He was said to be either a Jordanian or Palestinian who obtained
Kenyan citizenship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The complaints unsealed Thursday dealt only with Salim, and
details of what charges Odeh would face were not immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan officials were said to be eager to seek justice for the
hundreds of Kenyan victims of the embassy bombing, but also wary
that a trial for an attack on a U.S. target in Kenya might invite
new terrorist assaults on Kenyan targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
