<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Manufacturer to Pack 400 Million Transistors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at a
Dallas-based company said Wednesday that they have developed
leading-edge semiconductor technology based on the smallest
announced transistors in the industry.
</P>
<P>
Featuring an effective channel length of 0.07 micron -- 1,000
times thinner than a human hair -- the transistors are so
miniscule that more than 400 million of them will fit onto a
single chip the size of a fingernail, said Texas Instrument in the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
"The ability to pack 400 million transistors on single,
low-voltage chip will push high-speed wireless and multimedia
communications far beyond the limits of today's technology," said
the new semiconductor company focused primarily on digital signal
processing solutions.
</P>
<P>
The process will enable operating frequencies exceeding
1-gigahertz with internal voltages as low as 1 volt, and support
input/output signaling environments of up to 3.3 volts.
</P>
<P>
The 0.07-micron transistors are designed for analog operating
as well as digital. As a result, the company will be able to
integrate mixed-signal functions along with high-speed digital
logic and cores from the very beginning of the process life cycle.
Products based on these chips will weigh less, shrink in size,
consume less power and be able to execute software much faster
than today's technology.
</P>
<P>
By using the chips, certain types of hearing aids may be
reduced to appliances that can be directly implanted in the inner
ear. Wireless telephones will be able to handle data and video as
well as voice. Modems operating on asymmetric digital subscriber
line (ADSL) will bring no-wait Internet access to consumers and
small businesses. Hard disk drives will read gigabits of data per
second for instantaneous access of large data bases.
</P>
<P>
The Texas manufacturer said that it plans to initiate designs
in the new 0.07-micron chip starting in the year 2000, with volume
production beginning in 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
