<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Shows No Erosion Sign Among Democratic Voters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Despite Democratic leaders'
worry that fallout from the Lewinsky affair could cause their
party's voters to stay home in the mid-term election in November,
a new poll shows no sign of erosion among Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, we don't see any less interest in Democratic voters
with regard to turnout, even though the public is more critical of
Bill Clinton personally than it has been," said Andrew Kohut,
director of the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press,
which released its poll Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Pew poll, 61 percent say the Clinton-Lewinsky
controversy will not affect their vote in November.
</P>
<P>
Still, Republicans say they are seeing the first signs that the
president's problems could dampen Democratic turnout this fall.
</P>
<P>
"The Democrats are not as likely to be interested in the
election, they are less intense about voting and about supporting
their candidate," said Republican pollster Ed Goeas, citing his
detailed Republican survey of voter intensity. But Democratic
pollster Geoff Garin countered it's too early to get a significant
reading of such matters.
</P>
<P>
Much will depend on the contents of an expected report from
special prosecutor Kenneth Starr and the president's handling of
the situation, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Pew poll suggested Democrats and Republicans are closely
matched in this fall's congressional elections, with Republicans
still having a slight edge among likely voters. And it reflected
no significant change in voter enthusiasm for either party since
June.
</P>
<P>
The president's job approval rating was steady at 62 percent,
and a majority of those surveyed would have an unfavorable view of
any member of Congress who voted for impeachment hearings for the
president.
</P>
<P>
But the poll had some potential trouble signs as well. A
majority said the controversy was severe enough that it was
interfering with Clinton's ability to run the country. And 43
percent said he did not have the respect he needs from officials
in Washington and world leaders to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
"This is potentially a sign of vulnerability," Kohut said,
noting those issues are related to Clinton's job and not to him
personally. "This could lead to a more serious loss of political
support than the feelings about whether he was telling the truth."
</P>
<P>
The phone survey of 1,001 adults taken from Friday through
Monday has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
