<DOCNO> XIE19980828.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President to Visit Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
will visit Cyprus later this year, the first by an Israeli head of
state since the establishment of the diplomatic relationship in
1960.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the visit here Thursday, Israeli Ambassador to
Cyprus Shemi Tzur said during the visit, Weizman and his Cypriot
counterpart Glafcos Clerides will discuss how to upgrade relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tzur did not dislose the exact date of the visit.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus-Israel relations could have never been termed as
warm until after Israel reached Oslo peace agreement with the
Palestinians in 1993 and triggered off a period of rapprochement
with its Arab and pro-Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus did not receive an Israeli foreign minister until July
1994 when Simon Peres' visit was described as a milestone in the
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that during Weizman's visit, Cyprus will raise
the issue of the close Israel-Turkey defense ties.
</P>
<P>
Turkey reached two defense-related agreements with Israel in
1996. Its close defense cooperation with the Jewish country has
triggered strong criticism from its neighbors, particularly Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey took over the northern third of the Cypriot island in
1974 after a pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots and stations at
least 35,000 troops there to support a breakaway Turkish Cypriot
regime.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli leaders have explained that the defense ties with
Turkey are not directed against a third country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Cypriot Minister of Commerce,
Industry and Tourism Nicos Rolandis, Tzur hoped that more Israeli
tourists will visit Cyprus this year.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 40,000 Israelis visited
Cyprus in 1996, while the respective number for 1990 was only
8,400. 
</P>
</TEXT>
