<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Plunge Appears in Turkish Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Affected by the economic crisis
in Russia and new taxes, the Istanbul Stock Exchange National-100
Index dropped a record 13.58 percent to 2,603.99 points on
Thursday, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The index fell as low as 2,580 points during Thursday
afternoon trading, and later made only a slight recovery.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the index tumbled 255.99 points, or 7.95 percent,
to close at 2,997.25 points.
</P>
<P>
Turkish investors fear that scores of Turkish companies which
trade with Russia will be severely damaged by Moscow's economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul stock market is especially sensitive to Russia's
financial situation due to close economic link between Turkey and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Turkish brokers said that the national-100 index plunged also
because of a withholding tax on interbanking money transactions,
a 12 percent tax on banking deposits and new charges on dividends
and share earnings.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Turkish Minister of Finance and Customs
Zekeriya Temizel as saying that "capital may flee to tax
shelters. There is nothing to stop this, but everyone should know
that the return of this capital from tax havens to Turkey will be
costly." 
</P>
</TEXT>
