<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses Weapons Inspector of Creating "Theory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq accused on Thursday U.N.
weapons inspector Scott Ritter of fabricating "the theory of
concealment" that had sparked a weapons inspection crisis in
February.
</P>
<P>
The government spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said that the theory was prepared by Israeli and American
intelligence agencies with the aim to push for an open-ended
course of "inspection, investigation and suspicion at all that
Iraq says, does and achieves."
</P>
<P>
The accusation of Iraqi government came after Ritter, who is
called by Iraq "American spy" and blocked access to some
inspection sites, resigned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"This American officer had been the spearhead in implementing
the biggest U.S. lie of Iraq's concealment of proscribed weapons,
materials and documents at presidential sites," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The presidential incident has led to a standoff between the
U.N. weapons inspectors and Iraq, in which the U.S. and Britain
massed a large force in the Gulf to force Baghdad to open all its
presidential palaces for weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was defused after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
reached an agreement with Baghdad to allow access to all the
presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Special Committee (UNSCOM), which has taken charge of
weapons inspections in Iraq since 1991 after the Gulf War, set off
by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, has long accused Iraq of concealing
banned weapons and documents and asked it to open all suspected
sites to weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq, which claims that it has eliminated all banned
weapons in line with relevant U.N. resolutions, has repeatedly
criticized the UNSCOM for serving the U.S. to attempt to prolong
the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will not be lifted until the UNSCOM certifies
that Iraq is rid of all banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
But the weapons inspections were bogged down again after Baghdad
suspended cooperation with UNSCOM and the International Atomic
Energy Agency on August 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
