<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2105GMT, August 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid
said Thursday that the Libyan consent to the U.S.-British proposal
on settling the Lockerbie issue is an "important step along the
road to end this problem for good."
</P>
<P>
Abdel Meguid, who is now in Lebanon, told Egypt's Middle East
News Agency that Libya's acceptance of the proposal was "expected"
as the proposal was in line with Libya's stance and an idea
presented by the AL three years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Libya's stand is flexible," Abdel Meguid said, urging the
United Nations to remove the six-year-old sanctions imposed on
Tripoli. (AL-Lockerbie Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat is not optimistic over the chances to advance the
stalled peace process, an Israeli legislator who met Arafat
Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting in the West Bank town of Ramallah, Arafat told
Israeli Labor Knesset (Parliament) Member Salah Tarif that based
on the conditions imposed by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, there is still a long way to go before an agreement
could be reached over the long overdue Israeli redeployment in the
West Bank, Israel Radio reported. (Arafat-Peace Process)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A total of 21 people were injured in the explosion
in Tel Aviv on Thursday morning, while both Israeli and
Palestinian leaders condemned the bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
The bomb hid in a garbage can went off at an intersection of
the bustling Allenby Street and Rothschild Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who went to Tel Aviv
in the afternoon to see the injured in hospitals, said the
explosion showed the terrorists were acting against Israeli
civilians not only in the West Bank city of Hebron but anywhere.
</P>
<P>
Arafat condemned Thursday's explosion, saying the Palestinians
condemn any kind of terrorist attacks, particularly these acts
against innocent civilians. (Israel-Bombing, 3rd lead-writethru)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab League Assistant Secretary General Ahmad Adel
Thursday underlined the necessity of giving Libya enough time to
study the U.S.-British proposal on settling the Libya-West
Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
Adel, speaking to Egypt's Middle East News Agency, said that he
underlined the importance of giving Libya time to consider
measures and get clarifications on this score during his meeting
Thursday with the political affairs department chief of
U.S. Embassy in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Adel said AL officials have held two rounds of talks with the
U.S. official since Wednesday on the U.S.-British initiative which
was announced on Monday. (AL-Lockerbie Bombing) 
</P>
</TEXT>
