<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shares Fall Sharply Across Europe With Growing Panic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Stock markets nosedived across
Europe Thursday, bowing to the weight of worsening crisis in
Russia and a general panic sweeping global markets.
</P>
<P>
While battered Western European markets closed with losses
between 3 and 6 percent, some bourses in Eastern Europe went down
by more 10 percent, as panicking investors rushed to unload
stocks. Hungary plunged 14 percent, Warsaw 6 percent, and Prague
slid 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Fears of global economic recession are growing as financial
authorities such as the IMF, used to fire-fighting one country's
crisis at a time, are being overwhelmed by the scale of capital
flight from emerging markets, according to market analysts.
</P>
<P>
Russia's central bank suspended foreign exchange trade of the
rouble on the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange Thursday after
opening trade showed a big drop was in store, intensifying
European investors' fears over what would be the worst to come.
</P>
<P>
"There's no obvious crisis management situation to deal with
this," observed Robin Marshall, head of research at U.S. bank
Chase in London. "There are a million investors all with positions
and the capital pressures are just too hard to resist."
</P>
<P>
Those who had hoped that Wall Street's usual optimism would
bail out shares elsewhere were disappointed to find that Wall
Street weighed in with an early 325 point loss, almost 4 percent,
which was considered to breach key technical support points if
maintained to the close.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Eastern Europe, however, an absence of buyers rather
than a weight of selling was evident in the Western bourses.
</P>
<P>
London's blue chip shares suffered another session of heavy
selling, with another 51 billion U.S. dollars wiped off share
values. The FTSE 100 lost 176.9 points to end the day at 5,368.5,
but finishing clear of the 5,353.5 session low.
</P>
<P>
Dealers warned that there were plenty more profits for
investors still to take. Volume improved on recent levels, with
over 800m shares traded by the close.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt shares lost 4.5 percent in electronic trade on the
Xetra DAX, once again worried about the exposure of German banks
to Russian debt. Paris lost 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Swiss shares were hit hard again after Wednesday's big losses,
losing 5.1 percent and dropping through chart support at the key
7,100 level on the Swiss Market Index. In Madrid, fears for Latin
America dragged the market down 5.9 percent by the close.
</P>
<P>
Other markets were similarly afflicted, with Athens ATX falling
5 percent, Stockholm's OMX index 4.15 percent down, Milan's Mibtel
losing 4.4 percent, Portugal's PSI20 dropping 6.13 percent, Oslo's
Total Index sliding 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
But, not everyone believes the end of the world is nigh. What
may yet be called a black Thursday by many was a ray of hope for
market contrarians.
</P>
<P>
Reuters quoted Dain Rauscher's Robert Dickey as saying that the
sense of panic entering the market was one of the signs
technicians look for as a harbinger of a market bottom.
</P>
<P>
"I feel pretty good we're making a bottom, and the fact that no
one believes me reinforces that," he said. "This is the way
bottoms are formed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
